Dialogue: 0,0:00:33.70,0:00:35.75,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Good morning and welcome to
Dialogue: 0,0:00:35.75,0:00:37.32,Default,,0,0,0,,your Apps and Evolving Network
Dialogue: 0,0:00:37.38,0:00:38.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Security Standards.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:38.85,0:00:41.09,Default,,0,0,0,,My name is Bailey Basile and I'm
Dialogue: 0,0:00:41.09,0:00:42.64,Default,,0,0,0,,secure transports engineer at
Dialogue: 0,0:00:42.64,0:00:43.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Apple.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:43.86,0:00:45.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Today, my colleague Chris and I
Dialogue: 0,0:00:45.41,0:00:46.97,Default,,0,0,0,,will be talking to you about the
Dialogue: 0,0:00:46.97,0:00:48.88,Default,,0,0,0,,ways that network security
Dialogue: 0,0:00:48.92,0:00:51.11,Default,,0,0,0,,standards change and how that
Dialogue: 0,0:00:51.11,0:00:52.62,Default,,0,0,0,,affects you and your apps.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:53.77,0:00:55.90,Default,,0,0,0,,We know that all of you care as
Dialogue: 0,0:00:55.90,0:00:57.94,Default,,0,0,0,,much about your users' privacy
Dialogue: 0,0:00:57.94,0:00:59.26,Default,,0,0,0,,and security as we do.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:59.26,0:01:01.45,Default,,0,0,0,,And that's why when you see
Dialogue: 0,0:01:01.45,0:01:04.23,Default,,0,0,0,,attacks like BEAST, and CRIME,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:04.31,0:01:06.66,Default,,0,0,0,,and DROWN, you worry about
Dialogue: 0,0:01:06.66,0:01:09.86,Default,,0,0,0,,whether your app is affected.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:10.34,0:01:13.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Unfortunately, all protocols
Dialogue: 0,0:01:13.48,0:01:15.86,Default,,0,0,0,,age, and as they are in the
Dialogue: 0,0:01:15.86,0:01:18.17,Default,,0,0,0,,public more attacks are found
Dialogue: 0,0:01:18.17,0:01:19.09,Default,,0,0,0,,over time.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:20.14,0:01:23.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Even worse, the algorithms upon
Dialogue: 0,0:01:23.36,0:01:26.91,Default,,0,0,0,,which these standards rely have
Dialogue: 0,0:01:26.91,0:01:29.35,Default,,0,0,0,,a built-in shelf life.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:29.84,0:01:32.13,Default,,0,0,0,,That means that as they age and
Dialogue: 0,0:01:32.21,0:01:34.89,Default,,0,0,0,,as computers get faster, those
Dialogue: 0,0:01:34.89,0:01:36.73,Default,,0,0,0,,algorithms become vulnerable to
Dialogue: 0,0:01:36.73,0:01:38.93,Default,,0,0,0,,attacks like collisions,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:39.35,0:01:41.70,Default,,0,0,0,,factorization and brute force.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:43.09,0:01:44.86,Default,,0,0,0,,When you hear about these scary
Dialogue: 0,0:01:44.90,0:01:47.29,Default,,0,0,0,,sounding attacks like a FLAME
Dialogue: 0,0:01:47.62,0:01:49.59,Default,,0,0,0,,and BREACH, and POODLE.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:49.59,0:01:51.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, maybe poodle doesn't sound
Dialogue: 0,0:01:51.14,0:01:51.69,Default,,0,0,0,,so scary.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:52.80,0:01:54.32,Default,,0,0,0,,When you hear about these scary
Dialogue: 0,0:01:54.32,0:01:56.86,Default,,0,0,0,,attacks, you wonder what you can
Dialogue: 0,0:01:56.86,0:01:59.34,Default,,0,0,0,,do to prevent your app from
Dialogue: 0,0:01:59.34,0:02:01.07,Default,,0,0,0,,appearing in the press the next
Dialogue: 0,0:02:01.41,0:02:03.15,Default,,0,0,0,,time a big attach happens.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:03.82,0:02:05.38,Default,,0,0,0,,And that's why today, I'm going
Dialogue: 0,0:02:05.38,0:02:06.74,Default,,0,0,0,,to be talking about some best
Dialogue: 0,0:02:06.74,0:02:09.47,Default,,0,0,0,,practices that you can follow in
Dialogue: 0,0:02:09.50,0:02:11.93,Default,,0,0,0,,order to ensure that your app is
Dialogue: 0,0:02:11.93,0:02:12.72,Default,,0,0,0,,not affected.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:13.17,0:02:14.99,Default,,0,0,0,,I'll also talk a little bit
Dialogue: 0,0:02:14.99,0:02:18.90,Default,,0,0,0,,about how Apple helps you by
Dialogue: 0,0:02:18.90,0:02:20.96,Default,,0,0,0,,removing insecure options from
Dialogue: 0,0:02:20.96,0:02:21.92,Default,,0,0,0,,our platforms.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:23.18,0:02:24.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Chris will then give you an
Dialogue: 0,0:02:24.47,0:02:26.36,Default,,0,0,0,,update on app transport
Dialogue: 0,0:02:26.40,0:02:28.16,Default,,0,0,0,,security, which is a mechanism
Dialogue: 0,0:02:28.16,0:02:30.74,Default,,0,0,0,,that you can use in your apps in
Dialogue: 0,0:02:30.74,0:02:32.29,Default,,0,0,0,,order to ensure that best
Dialogue: 0,0:02:32.29,0:02:33.86,Default,,0,0,0,,practices are enforced.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:35.24,0:02:36.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Finally, Chris will be giving
Dialogue: 0,0:02:36.92,0:02:39.47,Default,,0,0,0,,you a talk about Transport Layer
Dialogue: 0,0:02:39.47,0:02:42.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Security, or TLS and an exciting
Dialogue: 0,0:02:42.39,0:02:44.42,Default,,0,0,0,,new evolution in that protocol.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:45.44,0:02:46.97,Default,,0,0,0,,So, let's dive right into those
Dialogue: 0,0:02:47.01,0:02:48.05,Default,,0,0,0,,best practices.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:48.89,0:02:50.88,Default,,0,0,0,,I'll start at a high level.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:51.58,0:02:53.26,Default,,0,0,0,,First, the biggest thing you
Dialogue: 0,0:02:53.26,0:02:56.39,Default,,0,0,0,,have to remember, because as I
Dialogue: 0,0:02:56.39,0:02:58.48,Default,,0,0,0,,said, those protocols age, and
Dialogue: 0,0:02:58.48,0:03:00.38,Default,,0,0,0,,those standards have a built-in
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.38,0:03:03.19,Default,,0,0,0,,shelf life, you can't set and
Dialogue: 0,0:03:03.24,0:03:05.58,Default,,0,0,0,,forget the security of your app.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:06.49,0:03:08.25,Default,,0,0,0,,You have to go through on a
Dialogue: 0,0:03:08.25,0:03:10.89,Default,,0,0,0,,regular basis and make sure that
Dialogue: 0,0:03:10.89,0:03:12.39,Default,,0,0,0,,your app is up to date.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:12.81,0:03:14.93,Default,,0,0,0,,And to know what to change, you
Dialogue: 0,0:03:14.93,0:03:16.52,Default,,0,0,0,,should be following standards
Dialogue: 0,0:03:16.56,0:03:19.23,Default,,0,0,0,,bodies, academic research and
Dialogue: 0,0:03:19.23,0:03:21.51,Default,,0,0,0,,industry best practices.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:22.26,0:03:24.71,Default,,0,0,0,,But the good news for all of
Dialogue: 0,0:03:24.71,0:03:27.00,Default,,0,0,0,,you, is that you are already
Dialogue: 0,0:03:27.00,0:03:28.78,Default,,0,0,0,,doing this because you're here
Dialogue: 0,0:03:28.87,0:03:29.37,Default,,0,0,0,,today.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:30.62,0:03:34.08,Default,,0,0,0,,If you are a developer or a
Dialogue: 0,0:03:34.08,0:03:35.92,Default,,0,0,0,,library developer, you may be
Dialogue: 0,0:03:35.92,0:03:38.42,Default,,0,0,0,,using a third-party library in
Dialogue: 0,0:03:38.42,0:03:39.47,Default,,0,0,0,,your app.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:39.47,0:03:41.28,Default,,0,0,0,,And those can be very risky.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:41.78,0:03:42.99,Default,,0,0,0,,In particular, if you're
Dialogue: 0,0:03:42.99,0:03:44.23,Default,,0,0,0,,integrating a third-party
Dialogue: 0,0:03:44.23,0:03:46.14,Default,,0,0,0,,library you have to be sure you
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.23,0:03:47.25,Default,,0,0,0,,keep it up to date.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:47.70,0:03:49.38,Default,,0,0,0,,A library that you integrated
Dialogue: 0,0:03:49.49,0:03:52.16,Default,,0,0,0,,three years ago is already out
Dialogue: 0,0:03:52.16,0:03:54.58,Default,,0,0,0,,of date and maybe using weakened
Dialogue: 0,0:03:54.65,0:03:55.41,Default,,0,0,0,,security.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:55.64,0:03:57.45,Default,,0,0,0,,That means that your users are
Dialogue: 0,0:03:57.45,0:03:59.17,Default,,0,0,0,,not getting the security that
Dialogue: 0,0:03:59.17,0:03:59.77,Default,,0,0,0,,you want.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:01.46,0:04:04.10,Default,,0,0,0,,If you're using our APIs, we
Dialogue: 0,0:04:04.10,0:04:05.03,Default,,0,0,0,,help you here.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:05.39,0:04:07.40,Default,,0,0,0,,First, we remove many of the
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.40,0:04:10.15,Default,,0,0,0,,insecure options from our APIs
Dialogue: 0,0:04:10.42,0:04:12.41,Default,,0,0,0,,so that you aren't affected.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:13.76,0:04:15.59,Default,,0,0,0,,We also make available App
Dialogue: 0,0:04:15.85,0:04:18.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Transport Security, or ATS, in
Dialogue: 0,0:04:18.26,0:04:19.74,Default,,0,0,0,,order for you to be able to
Dialogue: 0,0:04:19.74,0:04:21.76,Default,,0,0,0,,enforce those best practices in
Dialogue: 0,0:04:21.76,0:04:23.99,Default,,0,0,0,,your app, as long as you are
Dialogue: 0,0:04:23.99,0:04:26.25,Default,,0,0,0,,avoiding ATS exceptions.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:27.99,0:04:29.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Finally, when those attacks
Dialogue: 0,0:04:29.69,0:04:32.24,Default,,0,0,0,,happen, before those attacks
Dialogue: 0,0:04:32.24,0:04:34.45,Default,,0,0,0,,happen you have to remind your
Dialogue: 0,0:04:34.48,0:04:37.31,Default,,0,0,0,,clients, investors and managers
Dialogue: 0,0:04:37.65,0:04:39.25,Default,,0,0,0,,that it is worth the maintenance
Dialogue: 0,0:04:39.30,0:04:42.13,Default,,0,0,0,,cost to update your app so that
Dialogue: 0,0:04:42.13,0:04:44.38,Default,,0,0,0,,when the next attack happens you
Dialogue: 0,0:04:44.38,0:04:46.53,Default,,0,0,0,,are not scrambling to remediate
Dialogue: 0,0:04:46.53,0:04:48.72,Default,,0,0,0,,the problem wasting time and
Dialogue: 0,0:04:48.72,0:04:51.54,Default,,0,0,0,,energy and money as your app
Dialogue: 0,0:04:52.17,0:04:56.52,Default,,0,0,0,,appears in the press named as
Dialogue: 0,0:04:56.63,0:04:59.09,Default,,0,0,0,,one of the bad apps.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:59.25,0:05:01.20,Default,,0,0,0,,So, let's take a look back at
Dialogue: 0,0:05:01.20,0:05:02.38,Default,,0,0,0,,those attacks I was talking
Dialogue: 0,0:05:02.38,0:05:03.08,Default,,0,0,0,,about earlier.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:04.05,0:05:05.25,Default,,0,0,0,,I'd like to go through some
Dialogue: 0,0:05:05.29,0:05:07.13,Default,,0,0,0,,detailed best practices that you
Dialogue: 0,0:05:07.13,0:05:08.81,Default,,0,0,0,,can use to avoid these attacks.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:09.35,0:05:11.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Specifically, in the area of
Dialogue: 0,0:05:11.04,0:05:13.51,Default,,0,0,0,,encryption, cryptographic
Dialogue: 0,0:05:13.51,0:05:17.78,Default,,0,0,0,,hashes, public keys, protocols,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:18.45,0:05:19.85,Default,,0,0,0,,and revocation.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:19.85,0:05:23.33,Default,,0,0,0,,So, let's start right off the
Dialogue: 0,0:05:23.33,0:05:24.55,Default,,0,0,0,,bat with encryption.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:25.38,0:05:27.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Encryption, as all of you know
Dialogue: 0,0:05:27.24,0:05:29.79,Default,,0,0,0,,is a mechanism that you can use
Dialogue: 0,0:05:29.79,0:05:32.00,Default,,0,0,0,,to prevent your users' data from
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.00,0:05:33.76,Default,,0,0,0,,being read by an attacker.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:34.88,0:05:36.56,Default,,0,0,0,,But unfortunately, some of the
Dialogue: 0,0:05:36.56,0:05:38.25,Default,,0,0,0,,algorithms that we've been using
Dialogue: 0,0:05:38.25,0:05:40.04,Default,,0,0,0,,for encryption for a long time
Dialogue: 0,0:05:40.40,0:05:42.54,Default,,0,0,0,,are vulnerable to attacks where
Dialogue: 0,0:05:42.54,0:05:46.23,Default,,0,0,0,,the key material or the plain
Dialogue: 0,0:05:46.23,0:05:48.14,Default,,0,0,0,,text could be recovered by an
Dialogue: 0,0:05:48.17,0:05:48.77,Default,,0,0,0,,attacker.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:49.13,0:05:51.10,Default,,0,0,0,,In particular, RC 4 is
Dialogue: 0,0:05:51.18,0:05:53.99,Default,,0,0,0,,vulnerable to an attack where
Dialogue: 0,0:05:53.99,0:05:55.90,Default,,0,0,0,,the key is recoverable within as
Dialogue: 0,0:05:55.90,0:05:57.65,Default,,0,0,0,,little as three days.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:58.64,0:06:00.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Furthermore, the CBC modes of
Dialogue: 0,0:06:00.91,0:06:04.86,Default,,0,0,0,,both Triple-DES and AES are
Dialogue: 0,0:06:04.86,0:06:06.82,Default,,0,0,0,,vulnerable to attacks like BEAST
Dialogue: 0,0:06:07.19,0:06:11.04,Default,,0,0,0,,and Lucky 13 that mean that the
Dialogue: 0,0:06:11.52,0:06:13.11,Default,,0,0,0,,algorithm is not providing the
Dialogue: 0,0:06:13.21,0:06:15.09,Default,,0,0,0,,same level of security as you
Dialogue: 0,0:06:15.09,0:06:18.65,Default,,0,0,0,,want your users to have.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:19.37,0:06:22.70,Default,,0,0,0,,We plan to remove both RC 4 and
Dialogue: 0,0:06:22.70,0:06:25.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Triple-DES from TLS across our
Dialogue: 0,0:06:25.40,0:06:26.86,Default,,0,0,0,,platforms in the future.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:27.24,0:06:29.92,Default,,0,0,0,,So, now is the time to upgrade.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.34,0:06:32.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Instead, you should be using
Dialogue: 0,0:06:33.00,0:06:34.53,Default,,0,0,0,,authenticated encryption
Dialogue: 0,0:06:34.53,0:06:37.21,Default,,0,0,0,,algorithm like AES-GCM or
Dialogue: 0,0:06:37.21,0:06:39.73,Default,,0,0,0,,ChaCha20/Poly1305.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:40.69,0:06:42.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Those will ensure that you have
Dialogue: 0,0:06:42.03,0:06:45.43,Default,,0,0,0,,both the best encryption and can
Dialogue: 0,0:06:45.43,0:06:47.52,Default,,0,0,0,,detect when that data has been
Dialogue: 0,0:06:47.52,0:06:48.20,Default,,0,0,0,,modified.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:49.31,0:06:50.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Speaking of modified data.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:51.13,0:06:52.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's talk now about
Dialogue: 0,0:06:52.16,0:06:53.83,Default,,0,0,0,,cryptographic hashes.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:54.03,0:06:56.52,Default,,0,0,0,,As you know, cryptographic
Dialogue: 0,0:06:56.52,0:06:58.45,Default,,0,0,0,,hashes are a mechanism that
Dialogue: 0,0:06:58.45,0:07:01.14,Default,,0,0,0,,allows you to detect when the
Dialogue: 0,0:07:01.14,0:07:03.56,Default,,0,0,0,,input data has been changed.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:04.02,0:07:05.72,Default,,0,0,0,,But unfortunately, some of the
Dialogue: 0,0:07:05.72,0:07:07.54,Default,,0,0,0,,cryptographic hash algorithms
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.59,0:07:09.90,Default,,0,0,0,,that we've been using are
Dialogue: 0,0:07:09.90,0:07:11.09,Default,,0,0,0,,vulnerable to what's called a
Dialogue: 0,0:07:11.09,0:07:11.86,Default,,0,0,0,,collision attack.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:12.54,0:07:14.13,Default,,0,0,0,,A collision attack is where two
Dialogue: 0,0:07:14.13,0:07:15.87,Default,,0,0,0,,different inputs produce the
Dialogue: 0,0:07:15.87,0:07:17.55,Default,,0,0,0,,exact same output.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:17.85,0:07:21.05,Default,,0,0,0,,And so, you can't tell when an
Dialogue: 0,0:07:21.62,0:07:23.61,Default,,0,0,0,,attacker has modified the data
Dialogue: 0,0:07:23.90,0:07:25.40,Default,,0,0,0,,because the hashes will be the
Dialogue: 0,0:07:25.48,0:07:25.99,Default,,0,0,0,,same.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.44,0:07:29.72,Default,,0,0,0,,In particular, both MD 5 and
Dialogue: 0,0:07:29.72,0:07:32.03,Default,,0,0,0,,SHA-1 have demonstrated
Dialogue: 0,0:07:32.03,0:07:32.64,Default,,0,0,0,,collision attacks.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:34.30,0:07:37.10,Default,,0,0,0,,In fact, an MD-5 collision was
Dialogue: 0,0:07:37.10,0:07:39.30,Default,,0,0,0,,used in the Flame malware in
Dialogue: 0,0:07:39.30,0:07:41.90,Default,,0,0,0,,order to bypass platform
Dialogue: 0,0:07:41.95,0:07:43.76,Default,,0,0,0,,security and gain access to
Dialogue: 0,0:07:43.76,0:07:44.83,Default,,0,0,0,,users' systems.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:45.54,0:07:48.51,Default,,0,0,0,,We removed trust in all MD-5
Dialogue: 0,0:07:48.59,0:07:50.10,Default,,0,0,0,,signed certificates across our
Dialogue: 0,0:07:50.16,0:07:52.17,Default,,0,0,0,,platforms in previous years.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:53.74,0:07:56.62,Default,,0,0,0,,SHA-1 just recently had an
Dialogue: 0,0:07:56.89,0:07:57.04,Default,,0,0,0,,attack.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:57.04,0:07:58.73,Default,,0,0,0,,The Shouted attack was performed
Dialogue: 0,0:07:59.17,0:08:01.66,Default,,0,0,0,,earlier this year, and so this
Dialogue: 0,0:08:01.66,0:08:03.40,Default,,0,0,0,,is the freshest information.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:03.86,0:08:06.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Knowing that the SHA-1 one
Dialogue: 0,0:08:06.93,0:08:08.52,Default,,0,0,0,,attack was imminent, we removed
Dialogue: 0,0:08:08.60,0:08:10.76,Default,,0,0,0,,trust in all SHA-1 signed
Dialogue: 0,0:08:10.76,0:08:13.45,Default,,0,0,0,,certificates for TLS servers
Dialogue: 0,0:08:13.90,0:08:16.94,Default,,0,0,0,,when connecting through WebKit
Dialogue: 0,0:08:17.07,0:08:18.13,Default,,0,0,0,,and Safari.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:19.03,0:08:20.38,Default,,0,0,0,,And we've seen such an
Dialogue: 0,0:08:20.38,0:08:23.35,Default,,0,0,0,,improvement in the disk use of
Dialogue: 0,0:08:23.35,0:08:25.70,Default,,0,0,0,,SHA-1 certificates, that today
Dialogue: 0,0:08:25.78,0:08:26.86,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm announcing that we're
Dialogue: 0,0:08:26.86,0:08:29.52,Default,,0,0,0,,removing trust across all TLS
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.72,0:08:32.02,Default,,0,0,0,,connections for SHA-1 signed
Dialogue: 0,0:08:32.06,0:08:32.72,Default,,0,0,0,,certificates.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:33.31,0:08:35.07,Default,,0,0,0,,I'll talk a little bit more
Dialogue: 0,0:08:35.07,0:08:36.62,Default,,0,0,0,,about how that affects you and
Dialogue: 0,0:08:36.62,0:08:38.30,Default,,0,0,0,,your app later on.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:39.32,0:08:41.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Instead, you should be using any
Dialogue: 0,0:08:41.22,0:08:44.30,Default,,0,0,0,,of the SHA-2 family of hashes in
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.30,0:08:46.75,Default,,0,0,0,,order to get that best security
Dialogue: 0,0:08:47.11,0:08:48.77,Default,,0,0,0,,and avoid these collision
Dialogue: 0,0:08:50.16,0:08:50.32,Default,,0,0,0,,attacks.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:50.61,0:08:51.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Next, I'd like to talk about
Dialogue: 0,0:08:52.05,0:08:52.79,Default,,0,0,0,,public keys.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:53.37,0:08:55.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Public keys, as you know, are a
Dialogue: 0,0:08:55.75,0:08:58.35,Default,,0,0,0,,mechanism that provides an
Dialogue: 0,0:08:58.35,0:09:00.75,Default,,0,0,0,,identity, a sort of identity for
Dialogue: 0,0:09:00.75,0:09:01.19,Default,,0,0,0,,you.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:01.49,0:09:03.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Such that other people can
Dialogue: 0,0:09:03.91,0:09:05.68,Default,,0,0,0,,verify that something you signed
Dialogue: 0,0:09:05.68,0:09:07.53,Default,,0,0,0,,was signed by you and not
Dialogue: 0,0:09:07.59,0:09:08.21,Default,,0,0,0,,someone else.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:08.94,0:09:11.26,Default,,0,0,0,,And can be used to send you
Dialogue: 0,0:09:11.26,0:09:14.03,Default,,0,0,0,,encrypted data that only you can
Dialogue: 0,0:09:14.03,0:09:15.91,Default,,0,0,0,,decrypt with your private key.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:16.96,0:09:19.65,Default,,0,0,0,,But unfortunately, RSA key sizes
Dialogue: 0,0:09:19.85,0:09:22.24,Default,,0,0,0,,smaller than 1024 bits are
Dialogue: 0,0:09:22.24,0:09:25.86,Default,,0,0,0,,vulnerable to factorization
Dialogue: 0,0:09:25.92,0:09:26.17,Default,,0,0,0,,attacks.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:27.23,0:09:30.57,Default,,0,0,0,,In particular, a 768-bit RSA key
Dialogue: 0,0:09:30.57,0:09:33.97,Default,,0,0,0,,was factored back in 2009 and
Dialogue: 0,0:09:34.48,0:09:36.81,Default,,0,0,0,,that's why we removed trust from
Dialogue: 0,0:09:36.87,0:09:39.44,Default,,0,0,0,,any certificates using key sizes
Dialogue: 0,0:09:39.54,0:09:42.87,Default,,0,0,0,,smaller than 1024 bit RSA back
Dialogue: 0,0:09:42.87,0:09:44.96,Default,,0,0,0,,in the spring of 2016.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:46.22,0:09:49.92,Default,,0,0,0,,But the reality is even 1024 bit
Dialogue: 0,0:09:49.92,0:09:52.86,Default,,0,0,0,,RSA key sizes are not good
Dialogue: 0,0:09:52.86,0:09:53.23,Default,,0,0,0,,enough.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:53.57,0:09:55.80,Default,,0,0,0,,And we expect that an attack on
Dialogue: 0,0:09:55.80,0:09:58.87,Default,,0,0,0,,a 1024 bit RSA key is imminent.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:59.22,0:10:02.56,Default,,0,0,0,,And that's why today I'm
Dialogue: 0,0:10:02.56,0:10:04.14,Default,,0,0,0,,announcing that we're removing
Dialogue: 0,0:10:04.14,0:10:06.84,Default,,0,0,0,,trust from certificates using
Dialogue: 0,0:10:06.91,0:10:09.35,Default,,0,0,0,,key sizes smaller than 2048 bits
Dialogue: 0,0:10:09.76,0:10:11.98,Default,,0,0,0,,across all TLS connections to
Dialogue: 0,0:10:11.98,0:10:12.55,Default,,0,0,0,,servers.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:13.50,0:10:15.41,Default,,0,0,0,,In order to avoid these removals
Dialogue: 0,0:10:15.87,0:10:18.59,Default,,0,0,0,,and ensure that you have best
Dialogue: 0,0:10:18.73,0:10:20.60,Default,,0,0,0,,security, you should be using
Dialogue: 0,0:10:20.66,0:10:22.99,Default,,0,0,0,,RSA key sizes greater than or
Dialogue: 0,0:10:23.04,0:10:26.53,Default,,0,0,0,,equal to 2048 bits, or any of
Dialogue: 0,0:10:26.53,0:10:27.97,Default,,0,0,0,,the elliptic curves that are
Dialogue: 0,0:10:27.97,0:10:29.92,Default,,0,0,0,,trusted on our platforms.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:30.58,0:10:33.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Next, I'd like to spend some
Dialogue: 0,0:10:33.40,0:10:34.92,Default,,0,0,0,,time talking about protocols.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:36.14,0:10:38.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Protocols, as you know, are the
Dialogue: 0,0:10:38.70,0:10:40.96,Default,,0,0,0,,mechanism that you actually use
Dialogue: 0,0:10:40.96,0:10:42.44,Default,,0,0,0,,to talk to servers.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:42.80,0:10:44.20,Default,,0,0,0,,They are interoperable, which
Dialogue: 0,0:10:44.20,0:10:45.35,Default,,0,0,0,,means that you don't have to
Dialogue: 0,0:10:45.35,0:10:47.34,Default,,0,0,0,,worry whether the server you're
Dialogue: 0,0:10:47.34,0:10:49.31,Default,,0,0,0,,talking to across the world
Dialogue: 0,0:10:49.70,0:10:51.09,Default,,0,0,0,,supports the protocol you're
Dialogue: 0,0:10:51.09,0:10:51.67,Default,,0,0,0,,using.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:52.66,0:10:53.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Unfortunately, some of these
Dialogue: 0,0:10:54.03,0:10:58.03,Default,,0,0,0,,protocols are weak or provide no
Dialogue: 0,0:10:58.14,0:10:59.89,Default,,0,0,0,,security in particular.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:59.89,0:11:02.72,Default,,0,0,0,,If you are using http all of
Dialogue: 0,0:11:02.72,0:11:04.33,Default,,0,0,0,,your users' data is being
Dialogue: 0,0:11:04.33,0:11:05.94,Default,,0,0,0,,transmitted in the clear.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:06.37,0:11:08.11,Default,,0,0,0,,That means that anyone listening
Dialogue: 0,0:11:08.11,0:11:10.00,Default,,0,0,0,,in knows exactly that data.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:11.29,0:11:13.80,Default,,0,0,0,,But some of the older TLS
Dialogue: 0,0:11:14.16,0:11:16.36,Default,,0,0,0,,versions, like SSL Version 3,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:16.84,0:11:20.99,Default,,0,0,0,,TLS 1.0, and TLS 1.1 are also
Dialogue: 0,0:11:20.99,0:11:23.09,Default,,0,0,0,,vulnerable to numerous attacks.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:24.22,0:11:26.43,Default,,0,0,0,,And so, you should be avoiding
Dialogue: 0,0:11:26.43,0:11:28.75,Default,,0,0,0,,these when you configure your
Dialogue: 0,0:11:28.75,0:11:29.35,Default,,0,0,0,,servers.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:30.01,0:11:32.66,Default,,0,0,0,,We removed the use of SSL
Dialogue: 0,0:11:32.66,0:11:36.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Version 3 back in fall of 2015.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:36.14,0:11:37.79,Default,,0,0,0,,So, you've been protected on
Dialogue: 0,0:11:38.01,0:11:39.39,Default,,0,0,0,,that count for a while.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:40.31,0:11:42.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Instead, you should be using
Dialogue: 0,0:11:42.52,0:11:47.15,Default,,0,0,0,,HTTPS, that is HTTP over TLS,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:47.77,0:11:50.25,Default,,0,0,0,,with TLS 1.2.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:50.85,0:11:53.27,Default,,0,0,0,,TLS 1.2 is the current best
Dialogue: 0,0:11:53.63,0:11:56.64,Default,,0,0,0,,standard available for TLS
Dialogue: 0,0:11:56.89,0:11:57.50,Default,,0,0,0,,security.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:58.15,0:11:59.38,Default,,0,0,0,,But I'm pleased to announce
Dialogue: 0,0:11:59.38,0:12:00.88,Default,,0,0,0,,today that we're adding support
Dialogue: 0,0:12:00.88,0:12:03.17,Default,,0,0,0,,for the draft specification of
Dialogue: 0,0:12:03.35,0:12:04.71,Default,,0,0,0,,TLS 1.3.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:05.59,0:12:07.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Chris will be talking more about
Dialogue: 0,0:12:07.41,0:12:08.70,Default,,0,0,0,,that a little bit later.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:10.13,0:12:11.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Finally, I'd like to talk about
Dialogue: 0,0:12:12.19,0:12:13.08,Default,,0,0,0,,revocation.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:13.69,0:12:15.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Revocation is the mechanism that
Dialogue: 0,0:12:15.65,0:12:18.55,Default,,0,0,0,,clients use to verify the
Dialogue: 0,0:12:18.55,0:12:19.92,Default,,0,0,0,,certificate and determine
Dialogue: 0,0:12:19.92,0:12:21.33,Default,,0,0,0,,whether that certificate should
Dialogue: 0,0:12:21.33,0:12:23.95,Default,,0,0,0,,be trusted in the event that a
Dialogue: 0,0:12:23.95,0:12:27.00,Default,,0,0,0,,certificate is mishandled or
Dialogue: 0,0:12:27.48,0:12:28.30,Default,,0,0,0,,missed issued.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:28.90,0:12:31.04,Default,,0,0,0,,And of course, the worst thing
Dialogue: 0,0:12:31.04,0:12:32.64,Default,,0,0,0,,you can do in the area of
Dialogue: 0,0:12:32.64,0:12:36.75,Default,,0,0,0,,revocation is not check it.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:36.88,0:12:39.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Unfortunately, our platforms do
Dialogue: 0,0:12:39.47,0:12:41.90,Default,,0,0,0,,not check revocation by default
Dialogue: 0,0:12:42.03,0:12:44.18,Default,,0,0,0,,currently and I'll explain why
Dialogue: 0,0:12:44.41,0:12:44.90,Default,,0,0,0,,later.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:45.61,0:12:48.20,Default,,0,0,0,,That is, unless of course you
Dialogue: 0,0:12:48.20,0:12:50.27,Default,,0,0,0,,are using OCSP Stapling.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:50.80,0:12:53.14,Default,,0,0,0,,OCSP being the Online
Dialogue: 0,0:12:53.23,0:12:55.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Certificate Status Protocol.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:55.53,0:12:57.61,Default,,0,0,0,,If your servers are using OCSP
Dialogue: 0,0:12:57.61,0:13:00.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Stapling, your certificates are
Dialogue: 0,0:13:00.89,0:13:02.12,Default,,0,0,0,,always being checked for
Dialogue: 0,0:13:02.12,0:13:02.87,Default,,0,0,0,,revocation.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:03.71,0:13:05.65,Default,,0,0,0,,So, let's drill down into how
Dialogue: 0,0:13:05.65,0:13:09.33,Default,,0,0,0,,OCSP and OCSP Stapling work.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:10.04,0:13:13.60,Default,,0,0,0,,First, as usual, a server
Dialogue: 0,0:13:13.78,0:13:15.91,Default,,0,0,0,,requests a certificate from a
Dialogue: 0,0:13:16.13,0:13:17.82,Default,,0,0,0,,trusted third-party called a
Dialogue: 0,0:13:17.88,0:13:18.97,Default,,0,0,0,,certificate authority.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:19.76,0:13:22.21,Default,,0,0,0,,The server then uses that
Dialogue: 0,0:13:22.21,0:13:24.31,Default,,0,0,0,,certificate to identify itself
Dialogue: 0,0:13:24.37,0:13:26.68,Default,,0,0,0,,to clients connecting to it.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:27.38,0:13:29.49,Default,,0,0,0,,The client, in order to verify
Dialogue: 0,0:13:29.49,0:13:32.41,Default,,0,0,0,,that identity, then requests
Dialogue: 0,0:13:32.72,0:13:34.80,Default,,0,0,0,,information as to the status of
Dialogue: 0,0:13:34.80,0:13:36.70,Default,,0,0,0,,that certificate from the
Dialogue: 0,0:13:36.77,0:13:38.14,Default,,0,0,0,,certificate authority.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:38.81,0:13:39.98,Default,,0,0,0,,The certificate authority
Dialogue: 0,0:13:39.98,0:13:41.88,Default,,0,0,0,,replies back with a signed
Dialogue: 0,0:13:42.03,0:13:44.68,Default,,0,0,0,,message indicating the status of
Dialogue: 0,0:13:44.68,0:13:46.00,Default,,0,0,0,,the certificate that the client
Dialogue: 0,0:13:46.00,0:13:47.63,Default,,0,0,0,,is looking at.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:47.81,0:13:49.10,Default,,0,0,0,,The client verifies that
Dialogue: 0,0:13:49.10,0:13:50.92,Default,,0,0,0,,response and then uses that
Dialogue: 0,0:13:51.21,0:13:53.37,Default,,0,0,0,,status to determine whether to
Dialogue: 0,0:13:53.37,0:13:55.36,Default,,0,0,0,,continue the connection to the
Dialogue: 0,0:13:55.45,0:13:55.84,Default,,0,0,0,,server.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:56.81,0:13:59.52,Default,,0,0,0,,But unfortunately, OCSP has some
Dialogue: 0,0:13:59.52,0:14:00.08,Default,,0,0,0,,drawbacks.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:00.93,0:14:02.64,Default,,0,0,0,,As you can see from that
Dialogue: 0,0:14:02.90,0:14:04.74,Default,,0,0,0,,previous description It requires
Dialogue: 0,0:14:04.74,0:14:06.85,Default,,0,0,0,,an additional network connection
Dialogue: 0,0:14:07.20,0:14:08.90,Default,,0,0,0,,for every connection to the
Dialogue: 0,0:14:08.90,0:14:09.45,Default,,0,0,0,,server.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:10.73,0:14:12.81,Default,,0,0,0,,That means that your connections
Dialogue: 0,0:14:12.81,0:14:15.35,Default,,0,0,0,,in your apps appear slower and
Dialogue: 0,0:14:15.35,0:14:17.70,Default,,0,0,0,,none of us want that.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:18.15,0:14:20.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Furthermore, OCSP is performed
Dialogue: 0,0:14:20.88,0:14:21.84,Default,,0,0,0,,in the clear.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:22.31,0:14:23.62,Default,,0,0,0,,That means that all of the
Dialogue: 0,0:14:24.03,0:14:25.17,Default,,0,0,0,,traffic indicating which
Dialogue: 0,0:14:25.21,0:14:27.02,Default,,0,0,0,,certificate the client wants
Dialogue: 0,0:14:27.05,0:14:29.31,Default,,0,0,0,,checked is visible to anybody
Dialogue: 0,0:14:29.46,0:14:30.22,Default,,0,0,0,,watching.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:30.71,0:14:33.08,Default,,0,0,0,,And the reason that OCSP is
Dialogue: 0,0:14:33.08,0:14:35.37,Default,,0,0,0,,performed in the clear is that
Dialogue: 0,0:14:36.03,0:14:37.82,Default,,0,0,0,,it you would need it to
Dialogue: 0,0:14:37.82,0:14:40.14,Default,,0,0,0,,establish a secure connection.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:40.30,0:14:41.75,Default,,0,0,0,,So, if you had to establish a
Dialogue: 0,0:14:41.81,0:14:44.49,Default,,0,0,0,,secure connection to get OCSP,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:44.66,0:14:46.05,Default,,0,0,0,,you might end up in a circular
Dialogue: 0,0:14:46.05,0:14:46.65,Default,,0,0,0,,problem.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:47.27,0:14:49.79,Default,,0,0,0,,That's why OCSP is a huge
Dialogue: 0,0:14:49.79,0:14:51.39,Default,,0,0,0,,compromise of your users'
Dialogue: 0,0:14:51.43,0:14:52.16,Default,,0,0,0,,privacy.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:52.64,0:14:54.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Since all that information is in
Dialogue: 0,0:14:54.15,0:14:54.72,Default,,0,0,0,,the clear.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:55.32,0:14:57.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Anyone who is listening can and
Dialogue: 0,0:14:57.63,0:14:59.30,Default,,0,0,0,,find out what servers that
Dialogue: 0,0:14:59.41,0:15:00.79,Default,,0,0,0,,client is connecting to.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:01.48,0:15:03.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Furthermore, that third-party
Dialogue: 0,0:15:03.48,0:15:06.01,Default,,0,0,0,,certificate authority can
Dialogue: 0,0:15:06.01,0:15:08.51,Default,,0,0,0,,aggregate data as to which IP
Dialogue: 0,0:15:08.51,0:15:10.29,Default,,0,0,0,,address is which clients are
Dialogue: 0,0:15:10.29,0:15:13.37,Default,,0,0,0,,talking to which servers and
Dialogue: 0,0:15:13.37,0:15:15.52,Default,,0,0,0,,sell that to anybody they want.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:15.52,0:15:18.57,Default,,0,0,0,,So, that's very bad.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:18.68,0:15:20.92,Default,,0,0,0,,These 2 drawbacks are the reason
Dialogue: 0,0:15:20.92,0:15:24.44,Default,,0,0,0,,that we do not have OCSP enabled
Dialogue: 0,0:15:24.44,0:15:25.26,Default,,0,0,0,,by default.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:25.93,0:15:28.16,Default,,0,0,0,,And if you wanted to enable OCSP
Dialogue: 0,0:15:28.16,0:15:30.57,Default,,0,0,0,,in your app you would have to
Dialogue: 0,0:15:30.57,0:15:33.79,Default,,0,0,0,,integrate additional APIs.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:34.44,0:15:37.00,Default,,0,0,0,,So, next I want to talk about
Dialogue: 0,0:15:37.18,0:15:39.13,Default,,0,0,0,,OCSP Stapling, which is a
Dialogue: 0,0:15:39.13,0:15:42.67,Default,,0,0,0,,dramatic improvement on OCSP and
Dialogue: 0,0:15:42.96,0:15:44.65,Default,,0,0,0,,an evolution in the protocol
Dialogue: 0,0:15:44.65,0:15:46.36,Default,,0,0,0,,that removes many of the
Dialogue: 0,0:15:46.36,0:15:48.33,Default,,0,0,0,,drawbacks of OCSP.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:49.15,0:15:51.12,Default,,0,0,0,,As before, the server gets a
Dialogue: 0,0:15:51.12,0:15:52.98,Default,,0,0,0,,certificate from the certificate
Dialogue: 0,0:15:52.98,0:15:53.55,Default,,0,0,0,,authority.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:54.34,0:15:56.65,Default,,0,0,0,,But before sending that
Dialogue: 0,0:15:56.65,0:15:58.54,Default,,0,0,0,,certificate to a client, the
Dialogue: 0,0:15:58.70,0:16:01.16,Default,,0,0,0,,server requests the OCSP
Dialogue: 0,0:16:01.16,0:16:04.26,Default,,0,0,0,,response from the certificate
Dialogue: 0,0:16:04.26,0:16:04.83,Default,,0,0,0,,authority.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:05.13,0:16:06.34,Default,,0,0,0,,And when it gets that signed
Dialogue: 0,0:16:06.34,0:16:08.96,Default,,0,0,0,,response back, the server
Dialogue: 0,0:16:08.96,0:16:11.22,Default,,0,0,0,,verifies it and then sends it
Dialogue: 0,0:16:11.22,0:16:13.31,Default,,0,0,0,,along with the certificate to
Dialogue: 0,0:16:13.31,0:16:13.85,Default,,0,0,0,,the client.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:14.65,0:16:16.76,Default,,0,0,0,,The client can then verify both
Dialogue: 0,0:16:16.79,0:16:18.43,Default,,0,0,0,,the certificate and the
Dialogue: 0,0:16:18.43,0:16:19.49,Default,,0,0,0,,revocation status
Dialogue: 0,0:16:19.64,0:16:20.75,Default,,0,0,0,,simultaneously.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:21.35,0:16:23.33,Default,,0,0,0,,So, this is a huge win, both in
Dialogue: 0,0:16:23.33,0:16:25.10,Default,,0,0,0,,terms of performance, because
Dialogue: 0,0:16:25.10,0:16:26.51,Default,,0,0,0,,you don't need that additional
Dialogue: 0,0:16:26.51,0:16:27.64,Default,,0,0,0,,network connection on your
Dialogue: 0,0:16:27.64,0:16:28.08,Default,,0,0,0,,client.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:28.73,0:16:31.24,Default,,0,0,0,,And in terms of privacy, because
Dialogue: 0,0:16:31.24,0:16:32.81,Default,,0,0,0,,the client doesn't have to
Dialogue: 0,0:16:32.81,0:16:35.22,Default,,0,0,0,,connect to a third party to find
Dialogue: 0,0:16:35.22,0:16:37.17,Default,,0,0,0,,out about the revocation status.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:38.55,0:16:41.35,Default,,0,0,0,,But even OCSP Stapling has some
Dialogue: 0,0:16:41.35,0:16:41.88,Default,,0,0,0,,drawbacks.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:42.83,0:16:44.95,Default,,0,0,0,,We've noted that despite
Dialogue: 0,0:16:44.95,0:16:46.96,Default,,0,0,0,,encouraging all of you to adopt
Dialogue: 0,0:16:46.96,0:16:48.56,Default,,0,0,0,,it on your servers, that
Dialogue: 0,0:16:48.56,0:16:50.23,Default,,0,0,0,,adoption has been slow.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:51.25,0:16:54.01,Default,,0,0,0,,We are aware that enabling OCSP
Dialogue: 0,0:16:54.01,0:16:56.70,Default,,0,0,0,,in some of the open source
Dialogue: 0,0:16:56.90,0:16:59.18,Default,,0,0,0,,server implementations does have
Dialogue: 0,0:16:59.18,0:16:59.61,Default,,0,0,0,,drawbacks.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:00.22,0:17:02.08,Default,,0,0,0,,But we, nonetheless, encourage
Dialogue: 0,0:17:02.08,0:17:05.15,Default,,0,0,0,,you to fix those issues and to
Dialogue: 0,0:17:05.15,0:17:07.81,Default,,0,0,0,,adopt OCSP in order to improve
Dialogue: 0,0:17:07.81,0:17:10.96,Default,,0,0,0,,the security and the speed of
Dialogue: 0,0:17:10.96,0:17:12.80,Default,,0,0,0,,your app.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:13.08,0:17:15.86,Default,,0,0,0,,But the worst thing about OCSP
Dialogue: 0,0:17:15.86,0:17:17.77,Default,,0,0,0,,is that it actually doesn't
Dialogue: 0,0:17:17.77,0:17:20.52,Default,,0,0,0,,protect users against malicious
Dialogue: 0,0:17:20.58,0:17:21.12,Default,,0,0,0,,servers.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:21.77,0:17:23.67,Default,,0,0,0,,In particular, the malicious
Dialogue: 0,0:17:23.67,0:17:26.20,Default,,0,0,0,,server just need omit the
Dialogue: 0,0:17:26.20,0:17:28.62,Default,,0,0,0,,stapled OCSP response and the
Dialogue: 0,0:17:28.62,0:17:31.28,Default,,0,0,0,,client will never know that that
Dialogue: 0,0:17:31.28,0:17:33.02,Default,,0,0,0,,malicious server has a revoked
Dialogue: 0,0:17:33.02,0:17:33.79,Default,,0,0,0,,certificate.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:35.11,0:17:36.45,Default,,0,0,0,,That's why I'm pleased to
Dialogue: 0,0:17:36.45,0:17:39.07,Default,,0,0,0,,announce to you today that we
Dialogue: 0,0:17:39.07,0:17:41.95,Default,,0,0,0,,are enhancing revocation across
Dialogue: 0,0:17:41.95,0:17:43.27,Default,,0,0,0,,all of our platforms.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:43.93,0:17:46.26,Default,,0,0,0,,And it starts with us.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:46.75,0:17:49.13,Default,,0,0,0,,First, we gather information
Dialogue: 0,0:17:49.29,0:17:51.18,Default,,0,0,0,,from certificate transparency
Dialogue: 0,0:17:51.18,0:17:51.65,Default,,0,0,0,,logs.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:52.15,0:17:54.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Certificate transparency logs or
Dialogue: 0,0:17:54.36,0:17:58.26,Default,,0,0,0,,CT logs contain cryptographic
Dialogue: 0,0:17:58.34,0:18:00.38,Default,,0,0,0,,proofs of the existence of a
Dialogue: 0,0:18:00.46,0:18:01.14,Default,,0,0,0,,certificate.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:01.76,0:18:04.17,Default,,0,0,0,,You can find out more about CT
Dialogue: 0,0:18:04.54,0:18:06.86,Default,,0,0,0,,and how it works and how you can
Dialogue: 0,0:18:06.86,0:18:08.34,Default,,0,0,0,,use it to enhance the security
Dialogue: 0,0:18:08.34,0:18:10.63,Default,,0,0,0,,of your app by watching last
Dialogue: 0,0:18:10.93,0:18:13.07,Default,,0,0,0,,year's "What's New in Security"
Dialogue: 0,0:18:13.15,0:18:13.67,Default,,0,0,0,,session.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:15.02,0:18:16.70,Default,,0,0,0,,We use the information from the
Dialogue: 0,0:18:16.75,0:18:18.97,Default,,0,0,0,,certificate transparency logs to
Dialogue: 0,0:18:19.05,0:18:21.06,Default,,0,0,0,,find out about all of the
Dialogue: 0,0:18:21.06,0:18:22.65,Default,,0,0,0,,certificates that are trusted on
Dialogue: 0,0:18:22.65,0:18:23.52,Default,,0,0,0,,our platforms.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:23.87,0:18:25.41,Default,,0,0,0,,And if you want to help us
Dialogue: 0,0:18:25.63,0:18:28.09,Default,,0,0,0,,gather information about your
Dialogue: 0,0:18:28.09,0:18:29.81,Default,,0,0,0,,certificates in your apps and
Dialogue: 0,0:18:29.81,0:18:32.25,Default,,0,0,0,,your servers, you should verify
Dialogue: 0,0:18:32.65,0:18:34.29,Default,,0,0,0,,that your certificates are
Dialogue: 0,0:18:34.29,0:18:35.94,Default,,0,0,0,,logged to a CT log.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:36.57,0:18:39.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Many CA's will do this for you
Dialogue: 0,0:18:39.18,0:18:41.89,Default,,0,0,0,,so you just need check.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:42.78,0:18:45.41,Default,,0,0,0,,With that information, we now
Dialogue: 0,0:18:45.41,0:18:47.21,Default,,0,0,0,,know all of the certificate
Dialogue: 0,0:18:47.21,0:18:50.13,Default,,0,0,0,,authorities that are trusted on
Dialogue: 0,0:18:50.47,0:18:52.06,Default,,0,0,0,,our platforms.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:52.22,0:18:54.34,Default,,0,0,0,,And from that information we can
Dialogue: 0,0:18:54.34,0:18:57.08,Default,,0,0,0,,request all of the revocation
Dialogue: 0,0:18:57.08,0:18:58.74,Default,,0,0,0,,information from those
Dialogue: 0,0:18:58.74,0:18:59.87,Default,,0,0,0,,certificate authorities.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:01.18,0:19:03.32,Default,,0,0,0,,We then gather all of that
Dialogue: 0,0:19:03.32,0:19:04.76,Default,,0,0,0,,revocation information back.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:05.56,0:19:07.57,Default,,0,0,0,,We aggregate it into a single
Dialogue: 0,0:19:07.57,0:19:09.80,Default,,0,0,0,,efficient bundle, and then make
Dialogue: 0,0:19:09.80,0:19:11.75,Default,,0,0,0,,it available to all of our
Dialogue: 0,0:19:11.75,0:19:12.14,Default,,0,0,0,,clients.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:13.73,0:19:15.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Those clients check in
Dialogue: 0,0:19:15.52,0:19:18.47,Default,,0,0,0,,periodically with us to get that
Dialogue: 0,0:19:18.47,0:19:20.47,Default,,0,0,0,,bundled revocation information,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:21.63,0:19:24.92,Default,,0,0,0,,and use that latest status
Dialogue: 0,0:19:25.02,0:19:27.39,Default,,0,0,0,,revocation information when
Dialogue: 0,0:19:27.75,0:19:30.05,Default,,0,0,0,,checking server certificates
Dialogue: 0,0:19:30.05,0:19:31.21,Default,,0,0,0,,that they are using.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:32.47,0:19:36.18,Default,,0,0,0,,If the client hits a certificate
Dialogue: 0,0:19:36.25,0:19:38.35,Default,,0,0,0,,that is listed there, the client
Dialogue: 0,0:19:38.35,0:19:40.44,Default,,0,0,0,,will then perform OCSP.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:40.77,0:19:43.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Unless of course your app is
Dialogue: 0,0:19:43.85,0:19:45.87,Default,,0,0,0,,using OCSP Stapling.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:47.12,0:19:49.59,Default,,0,0,0,,The client uses this to verify
Dialogue: 0,0:19:49.59,0:19:51.21,Default,,0,0,0,,that the certificate really is
Dialogue: 0,0:19:51.21,0:19:51.73,Default,,0,0,0,,revoked.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:51.73,0:19:54.44,Default,,0,0,0,,So, we think this is a dramatic
Dialogue: 0,0:19:54.44,0:19:56.34,Default,,0,0,0,,improvement on the existing
Dialogue: 0,0:19:56.41,0:19:58.25,Default,,0,0,0,,state of revocation on our
Dialogue: 0,0:19:58.25,0:19:58.99,Default,,0,0,0,,platforms.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:00.05,0:20:02.35,Default,,0,0,0,,It has a dramatic improvement in
Dialogue: 0,0:20:02.61,0:20:04.50,Default,,0,0,0,,the privacy compromise area.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:05.34,0:20:06.90,Default,,0,0,0,,The bundle that we provide of
Dialogue: 0,0:20:06.90,0:20:08.30,Default,,0,0,0,,revocation information is the
Dialogue: 0,0:20:08.30,0:20:10.00,Default,,0,0,0,,same across all of our clients
Dialogue: 0,0:20:10.16,0:20:11.76,Default,,0,0,0,,and all of our platforms.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:12.22,0:20:15.11,Default,,0,0,0,,So, we never know which clients
Dialogue: 0,0:20:15.11,0:20:16.91,Default,,0,0,0,,are connecting to which servers.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:17.74,0:20:20.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Furthermore, only certificates
Dialogue: 0,0:20:20.02,0:20:23.64,Default,,0,0,0,,that are in that list require
Dialogue: 0,0:20:23.64,0:20:26.16,Default,,0,0,0,,the additional OCSP connection.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:27.57,0:20:30.95,Default,,0,0,0,,So, only the limited set of
Dialogue: 0,0:20:30.95,0:20:33.44,Default,,0,0,0,,certificates there risk that
Dialogue: 0,0:20:33.54,0:20:35.80,Default,,0,0,0,,additional privacy compromise if
Dialogue: 0,0:20:35.98,0:20:38.08,Default,,0,0,0,,your servers are not using OCSP
Dialogue: 0,0:20:38.08,0:20:38.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Stapling.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:40.19,0:20:43.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Another huge advantage is that
Dialogue: 0,0:20:43.60,0:20:47.38,Default,,0,0,0,,the information is automatically
Dialogue: 0,0:20:47.52,0:20:48.22,Default,,0,0,0,,updated.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:49.17,0:20:50.32,Default,,0,0,0,,That means that the client
Dialogue: 0,0:20:50.60,0:20:52.95,Default,,0,0,0,,always have that freshest
Dialogue: 0,0:20:52.95,0:20:55.03,Default,,0,0,0,,revocation information available
Dialogue: 0,0:20:55.03,0:20:56.91,Default,,0,0,0,,to them when making all of their
Dialogue: 0,0:20:56.91,0:20:59.48,Default,,0,0,0,,connections and this means that
Dialogue: 0,0:20:59.48,0:21:01.16,Default,,0,0,0,,you also get this for free.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:01.49,0:21:03.20,Default,,0,0,0,,You don't need to make a single
Dialogue: 0,0:21:03.20,0:21:05.18,Default,,0,0,0,,API call to get this best
Dialogue: 0,0:21:05.18,0:21:07.91,Default,,0,0,0,,practice security and faster
Dialogue: 0,0:21:08.03,0:21:08.81,Default,,0,0,0,,connections.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:09.98,0:21:12.43,Default,,0,0,0,,So, I've covered a lot of ground
Dialogue: 0,0:21:12.43,0:21:14.04,Default,,0,0,0,,in the last 20 minutes and I'd
Dialogue: 0,0:21:14.04,0:21:16.35,Default,,0,0,0,,like to recall what we talked
Dialogue: 0,0:21:16.35,0:21:16.73,Default,,0,0,0,,about.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:17.39,0:21:19.64,Default,,0,0,0,,First we talked about encryption
Dialogue: 0,0:21:19.92,0:21:21.77,Default,,0,0,0,,and using authenticated
Dialogue: 0,0:21:21.77,0:21:24.86,Default,,0,0,0,,encryption ciphers in your
Dialogue: 0,0:21:24.95,0:21:25.96,Default,,0,0,0,,servers and your apps.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:27.11,0:21:29.84,Default,,0,0,0,,We talked about hashes and how
Dialogue: 0,0:21:29.84,0:21:33.24,Default,,0,0,0,,to avoid collision attacks.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:33.43,0:21:35.94,Default,,0,0,0,,We talked about public keys and
Dialogue: 0,0:21:35.94,0:21:38.34,Default,,0,0,0,,using strong public keys that
Dialogue: 0,0:21:38.34,0:21:40.97,Default,,0,0,0,,are not subject to
Dialogue: 0,0:21:41.06,0:21:42.18,Default,,0,0,0,,factorization.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:43.26,0:21:45.25,Default,,0,0,0,,We also talked about protocols
Dialogue: 0,0:21:45.25,0:21:47.83,Default,,0,0,0,,and using the latest protocols
Dialogue: 0,0:21:47.83,0:21:51.97,Default,,0,0,0,,like TLS 1.2 and HTTPS to secure
Dialogue: 0,0:21:51.97,0:21:53.27,Default,,0,0,0,,your apps.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:53.65,0:21:55.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Finally, we talked about
Dialogue: 0,0:21:55.32,0:21:57.92,Default,,0,0,0,,revocation and how you can
Dialogue: 0,0:21:57.92,0:22:00.28,Default,,0,0,0,,improve the security of your app
Dialogue: 0,0:22:00.49,0:22:03.19,Default,,0,0,0,,by using revocation and OCSP
Dialogue: 0,0:22:03.19,0:22:04.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Stapling on your servers, and
Dialogue: 0,0:22:04.74,0:22:06.51,Default,,0,0,0,,the ways in which we've helped
Dialogue: 0,0:22:06.51,0:22:08.60,Default,,0,0,0,,you with a brand-new revocation
Dialogue: 0,0:22:08.60,0:22:09.25,Default,,0,0,0,,mechanism.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:10.81,0:22:12.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, I promise you that I'd talk
Dialogue: 0,0:22:12.59,0:22:14.96,Default,,0,0,0,,a little bit more about those
Dialogue: 0,0:22:15.03,0:22:16.62,Default,,0,0,0,,trust removals that I announced
Dialogue: 0,0:22:16.70,0:22:17.23,Default,,0,0,0,,earlier.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:18.21,0:22:20.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's go back and recall what
Dialogue: 0,0:22:20.37,0:22:22.01,Default,,0,0,0,,those trust removals were.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:23.42,0:22:25.40,Default,,0,0,0,,First, I announced that we would
Dialogue: 0,0:22:25.40,0:22:28.68,Default,,0,0,0,,be removing trust in any SHA-1
Dialogue: 0,0:22:28.79,0:22:30.91,Default,,0,0,0,,signed certificate for
Dialogue: 0,0:22:30.91,0:22:32.79,Default,,0,0,0,,connections to TLS servers
Dialogue: 0,0:22:32.85,0:22:34.99,Default,,0,0,0,,across all of our platforms.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:35.91,0:22:37.82,Default,,0,0,0,,I also announced that we would
Dialogue: 0,0:22:37.82,0:22:39.36,Default,,0,0,0,,be removing trust in
Dialogue: 0,0:22:39.40,0:22:41.98,Default,,0,0,0,,certificates using key sizes
Dialogue: 0,0:22:42.14,0:22:46.45,Default,,0,0,0,,smaller than 2048 bit RSA, also
Dialogue: 0,0:22:46.45,0:22:48.27,Default,,0,0,0,,in all TLS connections to
Dialogue: 0,0:22:48.27,0:22:48.74,Default,,0,0,0,,servers.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:50.21,0:22:52.09,Default,,0,0,0,,If you are connecting to a
Dialogue: 0,0:22:52.21,0:22:55.98,Default,,0,0,0,,server using TLS that has one of
Dialogue: 0,0:22:55.98,0:22:58.26,Default,,0,0,0,,these weak certificates, your
Dialogue: 0,0:22:58.26,0:23:01.11,Default,,0,0,0,,app will fail to make that
Dialogue: 0,0:23:01.29,0:23:04.17,Default,,0,0,0,,connection on macOS High Sierra
Dialogue: 0,0:23:04.59,0:23:07.37,Default,,0,0,0,,and iOS 11, and watchOS 4 and
Dialogue: 0,0:23:07.59,0:23:09.00,Default,,0,0,0,,tvOS 11.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:09.84,0:23:13.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's back up and remind
Dialogue: 0,0:23:13.52,0:23:16.50,Default,,0,0,0,,ourselves what certificates this
Dialogue: 0,0:23:16.50,0:23:18.20,Default,,0,0,0,,trust removal does not affect
Dialogue: 0,0:23:18.63,0:23:19.93,Default,,0,0,0,,based on my description.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:20.87,0:23:23.88,Default,,0,0,0,,First, this does not affect root
Dialogue: 0,0:23:23.88,0:23:24.56,Default,,0,0,0,,certificates.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:25.61,0:23:27.47,Default,,0,0,0,,In particular, root certificates
Dialogue: 0,0:23:27.52,0:23:29.94,Default,,0,0,0,,are not subject to the type of
Dialogue: 0,0:23:29.98,0:23:31.38,Default,,0,0,0,,collision attacks that we are
Dialogue: 0,0:23:31.38,0:23:34.08,Default,,0,0,0,,worried about with the SHA-1.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:35.20,0:23:38.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Also, we already removed all
Dialogue: 0,0:23:38.53,0:23:40.12,Default,,0,0,0,,roots certificates using key
Dialogue: 0,0:23:40.12,0:23:43.03,Default,,0,0,0,,sizes smaller than 2048 bits
Dialogue: 0,0:23:43.50,0:23:46.00,Default,,0,0,0,,back in fall of 2015.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:46.23,0:23:47.67,Default,,0,0,0,,So, you've been protected there
Dialogue: 0,0:23:47.79,0:23:48.62,Default,,0,0,0,,for awhile.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:50.10,0:23:51.91,Default,,0,0,0,,These trust removals also do not
Dialogue: 0,0:23:51.91,0:23:53.83,Default,,0,0,0,,affect enterprise distributed
Dialogue: 0,0:23:53.83,0:23:55.97,Default,,0,0,0,,certificates through mobile
Dialogue: 0,0:23:55.97,0:23:57.82,Default,,0,0,0,,device management or MDM.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:58.50,0:24:00.49,Default,,0,0,0,,It also doesn't affect user
Dialogue: 0,0:24:00.49,0:24:02.63,Default,,0,0,0,,installed certificates through
Dialogue: 0,0:24:02.63,0:24:05.60,Default,,0,0,0,,mail, Safari or keychain access.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:06.77,0:24:08.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Finally, it also doesn't affect
Dialogue: 0,0:24:08.72,0:24:11.10,Default,,0,0,0,,client certificates when used
Dialogue: 0,0:24:11.34,0:24:13.52,Default,,0,0,0,,with mutual authentication in
Dialogue: 0,0:24:13.62,0:24:13.99,Default,,0,0,0,,TLS.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:15.20,0:24:16.78,Default,,0,0,0,,It's not that we're not worried
Dialogue: 0,0:24:16.85,0:24:19.08,Default,,0,0,0,,about attacks on the
Dialogue: 0,0:24:19.16,0:24:21.24,Default,,0,0,0,,certificates, we are.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:21.92,0:24:24.16,Default,,0,0,0,,But we know that it takes time
Dialogue: 0,0:24:24.83,0:24:26.89,Default,,0,0,0,,for enterprises and users to
Dialogue: 0,0:24:26.96,0:24:29.68,Default,,0,0,0,,update all of their certificates
Dialogue: 0,0:24:29.98,0:24:31.96,Default,,0,0,0,,and their infrastructures to use
Dialogue: 0,0:24:31.96,0:24:33.50,Default,,0,0,0,,the latest algorithms.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:33.92,0:24:35.35,Default,,0,0,0,,And so, we're giving them just a
Dialogue: 0,0:24:35.35,0:24:36.60,Default,,0,0,0,,little bit more time.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:37.45,0:24:39.94,Default,,0,0,0,,I promise that we will be
Dialogue: 0,0:24:39.94,0:24:41.09,Default,,0,0,0,,removing trust in those
Dialogue: 0,0:24:41.09,0:24:42.38,Default,,0,0,0,,certificates later on.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:42.71,0:24:44.90,Default,,0,0,0,,So now is the time to start
Dialogue: 0,0:24:44.90,0:24:46.52,Default,,0,0,0,,updating, not then.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:47.94,0:24:49.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, you're probably wondering
Dialogue: 0,0:24:49.51,0:24:51.04,Default,,0,0,0,,what this looks like.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:51.47,0:24:52.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Because if it's affecting your
Dialogue: 0,0:24:52.90,0:24:53.75,Default,,0,0,0,,app, you need to know.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:54.53,0:24:56.60,Default,,0,0,0,,If you are in Safari, you see an
Dialogue: 0,0:24:56.60,0:24:57.73,Default,,0,0,0,,error dialog that looks
Dialogue: 0,0:24:57.73,0:24:59.11,Default,,0,0,0,,something like this.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:59.73,0:25:01.78,Default,,0,0,0,,And if we drill into the
Dialogue: 0,0:25:01.84,0:25:04.06,Default,,0,0,0,,certificate pane, we see that
Dialogue: 0,0:25:04.06,0:25:06.14,Default,,0,0,0,,there's a specific error message
Dialogue: 0,0:25:06.18,0:25:08.42,Default,,0,0,0,,for these removed weak
Dialogue: 0,0:25:08.51,0:25:08.92,Default,,0,0,0,,certificates.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:08.92,0:25:11.62,Default,,0,0,0,,And that's how you will know if
Dialogue: 0,0:25:11.67,0:25:13.14,Default,,0,0,0,,you're connecting to such a
Dialogue: 0,0:25:13.14,0:25:13.77,Default,,0,0,0,,certificate.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:15.08,0:25:16.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, many of you are app
Dialogue: 0,0:25:16.65,0:25:18.21,Default,,0,0,0,,developers and so you care more
Dialogue: 0,0:25:18.21,0:25:19.35,Default,,0,0,0,,about what you're going to see
Dialogue: 0,0:25:19.35,0:25:20.09,Default,,0,0,0,,in the logs.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:20.09,0:25:21.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Because you may never connect to
Dialogue: 0,0:25:21.71,0:25:23.81,Default,,0,0,0,,this server through Safari.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:24.47,0:25:25.80,Default,,0,0,0,,If you're looking in the logs,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:26.05,0:25:28.04,Default,,0,0,0,,you're going to see an invalid
Dialogue: 0,0:25:28.17,0:25:33.09,Default,,0,0,0,,searching or -9807 SSL error in
Dialogue: 0,0:25:33.09,0:25:34.84,Default,,0,0,0,,your URL session or URL
Dialogue: 0,0:25:34.92,0:25:35.51,Default,,0,0,0,,connection.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:37.34,0:25:39.84,Default,,0,0,0,,There's only one thing that you
Dialogue: 0,0:25:39.84,0:25:41.64,Default,,0,0,0,,can do in order to fix this
Dialogue: 0,0:25:41.64,0:25:44.00,Default,,0,0,0,,problem and that is to have your
Dialogue: 0,0:25:44.00,0:25:46.46,Default,,0,0,0,,server administrators upgrade
Dialogue: 0,0:25:46.46,0:25:48.06,Default,,0,0,0,,their servers to use new
Dialogue: 0,0:25:48.13,0:25:48.99,Default,,0,0,0,,certificates.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:50.19,0:25:52.35,Default,,0,0,0,,The good news is that all
Dialogue: 0,0:25:52.41,0:25:54.02,Default,,0,0,0,,certificate authorities trusted
Dialogue: 0,0:25:54.09,0:25:57.15,Default,,0,0,0,,on our platforms only issue
Dialogue: 0,0:25:57.15,0:25:58.56,Default,,0,0,0,,certificates that are not
Dialogue: 0,0:25:58.80,0:26:01.45,Default,,0,0,0,,subject to these removals and
Dialogue: 0,0:26:01.45,0:26:03.20,Default,,0,0,0,,you can find a list of all of
Dialogue: 0,0:26:03.20,0:26:04.78,Default,,0,0,0,,the root certificates that are
Dialogue: 0,0:26:04.78,0:26:08.93,Default,,0,0,0,,trusted on our platforms at this
Dialogue: 0,0:26:09.03,0:26:09.15,Default,,0,0,0,,link.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:09.24,0:26:11.16,Default,,0,0,0,,So, we've covered quite a bit
Dialogue: 0,0:26:11.16,0:26:13.99,Default,,0,0,0,,more ground now and I think I at
Dialogue: 0,0:26:13.99,0:26:15.80,Default,,0,0,0,,least am wondering what should I
Dialogue: 0,0:26:15.80,0:26:18.66,Default,,0,0,0,,do when I go back to my office.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:18.66,0:26:21.63,Default,,0,0,0,,How can I ensure that I have
Dialogue: 0,0:26:21.63,0:26:23.06,Default,,0,0,0,,best security.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:23.53,0:26:24.76,Default,,0,0,0,,And the very first thing you
Dialogue: 0,0:26:24.76,0:26:26.92,Default,,0,0,0,,should do is check your
Dialogue: 0,0:26:26.92,0:26:29.03,Default,,0,0,0,,implementations, libraries and
Dialogue: 0,0:26:29.18,0:26:30.77,Default,,0,0,0,,servers against those best
Dialogue: 0,0:26:30.77,0:26:32.39,Default,,0,0,0,,practices that I've listed.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:33.07,0:26:34.65,Default,,0,0,0,,We even have that handy chart
Dialogue: 0,0:26:34.71,0:26:36.98,Default,,0,0,0,,that you can use to ensure that
Dialogue: 0,0:26:36.98,0:26:39.10,Default,,0,0,0,,you have those good algorithms.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:39.93,0:26:42.01,Default,,0,0,0,,If you're a server developer you
Dialogue: 0,0:26:42.01,0:26:43.66,Default,,0,0,0,,might actually have quite a bit
Dialogue: 0,0:26:43.66,0:26:46.42,Default,,0,0,0,,of work to do in order to ensure
Dialogue: 0,0:26:46.50,0:26:48.24,Default,,0,0,0,,you have the best security for
Dialogue: 0,0:26:48.39,0:26:49.30,Default,,0,0,0,,all of your clients.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:51.22,0:26:52.37,Default,,0,0,0,,You should go through and
Dialogue: 0,0:26:52.37,0:26:55.34,Default,,0,0,0,,replace any SHA-1 or weak RSA
Dialogue: 0,0:26:55.41,0:26:58.38,Default,,0,0,0,,key certificates so that your
Dialogue: 0,0:26:58.38,0:27:00.63,Default,,0,0,0,,clients will not see failures on
Dialogue: 0,0:27:00.76,0:27:01.79,Default,,0,0,0,,our platforms.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:02.51,0:27:04.55,Default,,0,0,0,,And if you haven't already, you
Dialogue: 0,0:27:04.55,0:27:06.82,Default,,0,0,0,,should upgrade your servers to
Dialogue: 0,0:27:06.82,0:27:09.95,Default,,0,0,0,,TLS 1.2 and one of those
Dialogue: 0,0:27:10.16,0:27:11.94,Default,,0,0,0,,authenticated encryption ciphers
Dialogue: 0,0:27:12.03,0:27:13.29,Default,,0,0,0,,that I listed earlier.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:14.76,0:27:16.99,Default,,0,0,0,,You should allow the client to
Dialogue: 0,0:27:16.99,0:27:19.51,Default,,0,0,0,,determine what order to use
Dialogue: 0,0:27:19.51,0:27:22.33,Default,,0,0,0,,those ciphers because the
Dialogue: 0,0:27:22.33,0:27:25.35,Default,,0,0,0,,clients may be optimizing to use
Dialogue: 0,0:27:25.35,0:27:27.81,Default,,0,0,0,,the best and fastest cipher as
Dialogue: 0,0:27:27.81,0:27:30.36,Default,,0,0,0,,opposed to one of the slower
Dialogue: 0,0:27:30.46,0:27:32.11,Default,,0,0,0,,equally secure ciphers.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:33.60,0:27:34.72,Default,,0,0,0,,If you haven't already should
Dialogue: 0,0:27:34.88,0:27:37.87,Default,,0,0,0,,also enable OCSP Stapling so
Dialogue: 0,0:27:37.87,0:27:40.17,Default,,0,0,0,,that you can be sure that all of
Dialogue: 0,0:27:40.17,0:27:42.56,Default,,0,0,0,,your clients always have up to
Dialogue: 0,0:27:42.56,0:27:44.44,Default,,0,0,0,,date revocation information and
Dialogue: 0,0:27:44.80,0:27:46.76,Default,,0,0,0,,don't have to make privacy
Dialogue: 0,0:27:46.76,0:27:48.87,Default,,0,0,0,,compromising additional network
Dialogue: 0,0:27:48.94,0:27:49.66,Default,,0,0,0,,connections.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:51.04,0:27:52.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Finally, in order to help us
Dialogue: 0,0:27:53.25,0:27:54.84,Default,,0,0,0,,with our new revocation
Dialogue: 0,0:27:54.84,0:27:56.75,Default,,0,0,0,,mechanism you should check that
Dialogue: 0,0:27:56.75,0:27:58.73,Default,,0,0,0,,your certificates are being logs
Dialogue: 0,0:27:58.73,0:28:00.50,Default,,0,0,0,,to a certificate transparency
Dialogue: 0,0:28:00.50,0:28:00.84,Default,,0,0,0,,log.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:02.17,0:28:04.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Now many of you are probably app
Dialogue: 0,0:28:04.42,0:28:05.10,Default,,0,0,0,,developers.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:05.99,0:28:07.62,Default,,0,0,0,,And the good news for you is
Dialogue: 0,0:28:07.62,0:28:09.93,Default,,0,0,0,,that you have only one job.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:10.82,0:28:13.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Our platform has made it easy to
Dialogue: 0,0:28:13.02,0:28:15.56,Default,,0,0,0,,adopt best practices and all you
Dialogue: 0,0:28:15.56,0:28:18.62,Default,,0,0,0,,have to do is avoid ATS
Dialogue: 0,0:28:18.91,0:28:19.80,Default,,0,0,0,,exceptions.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:19.98,0:28:22.03,Default,,0,0,0,,If you are using an ATS
Dialogue: 0,0:28:22.03,0:28:22.63,Default,,0,0,0,,exception.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:22.63,0:28:25.86,Default,,0,0,0,,You are saying that connection
Dialogue: 0,0:28:25.86,0:28:28.61,Default,,0,0,0,,should have weaker security than
Dialogue: 0,0:28:28.66,0:28:30.54,Default,,0,0,0,,our platform can enforce.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:31.31,0:28:34.72,Default,,0,0,0,,So, now Chris is going to talk
Dialogue: 0,0:28:34.72,0:28:36.24,Default,,0,0,0,,to you about app transport
Dialogue: 0,0:28:36.24,0:28:38.00,Default,,0,0,0,,security a little bit more and
Dialogue: 0,0:28:38.00,0:28:39.44,Default,,0,0,0,,give you an update on the
Dialogue: 0,0:28:39.44,0:28:40.68,Default,,0,0,0,,current status.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:41.11,0:28:41.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Chris.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:42.52,0:28:48.70,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:28:49.20,0:28:49.83,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Thank you, Bailey.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:49.83,0:28:51.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, continuing along this
Dialogue: 0,0:28:52.00,0:28:54.21,Default,,0,0,0,,thread of best practices, I want
Dialogue: 0,0:28:54.21,0:28:55.67,Default,,0,0,0,,to dive a little bit deeper into
Dialogue: 0,0:28:56.88,0:28:57.14,Default,,0,0,0,,ATS.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:57.14,0:28:57.96,Default,,0,0,0,,ATS for those that aren't
Dialogue: 0,0:28:57.96,0:28:59.13,Default,,0,0,0,,familiar is a feature we
Dialogue: 0,0:28:59.13,0:29:01.11,Default,,0,0,0,,released in iOS 9 and
Dialogue: 0,0:29:01.60,0:29:02.97,Default,,0,0,0,,[inaudible] aimed at increasing
Dialogue: 0,0:29:02.97,0:29:04.35,Default,,0,0,0,,the security and privacy of your
Dialogue: 0,0:29:04.35,0:29:05.13,Default,,0,0,0,,customers' data.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:05.80,0:29:09.11,Default,,0,0,0,,ATS ensures that most of the
Dialogue: 0,0:29:09.11,0:29:10.47,Default,,0,0,0,,application data sent over the
Dialogue: 0,0:29:10.47,0:29:11.81,Default,,0,0,0,,network is encrypted and
Dialogue: 0,0:29:11.81,0:29:12.83,Default,,0,0,0,,protected by default.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:14.72,0:29:16.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Basically, this means moving
Dialogue: 0,0:29:16.27,0:29:18.66,Default,,0,0,0,,away from insecure and legacy
Dialogue: 0,0:29:18.95,0:29:19.82,Default,,0,0,0,,HTP toward HTTPS.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:19.82,0:29:22.17,Default,,0,0,0,,And that means a couple things,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:22.94,0:29:25.08,Default,,0,0,0,,the first of which is to use the
Dialogue: 0,0:29:25.08,0:29:26.51,Default,,0,0,0,,latest standardized version TLS,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:26.75,0:29:27.64,Default,,0,0,0,,version 1.2.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:28.18,0:29:29.56,Default,,0,0,0,,This has been updated and
Dialogue: 0,0:29:29.56,0:29:31.26,Default,,0,0,0,,amended over the years to take
Dialogue: 0,0:29:31.26,0:29:32.85,Default,,0,0,0,,into account some of the attacks
Dialogue: 0,0:29:32.85,0:29:34.14,Default,,0,0,0,,that Bailey eluded to earlier.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:35.05,0:29:36.26,Default,,0,0,0,,It also means using strong
Dialogue: 0,0:29:36.26,0:29:36.89,Default,,0,0,0,,cryptography.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:37.65,0:29:39.31,Default,,0,0,0,,That means using block cyphers
Dialogue: 0,0:29:39.31,0:29:41.10,Default,,0,0,0,,like AES and hash functions from
Dialogue: 0,0:29:41.10,0:29:41.93,Default,,0,0,0,,the SHA-2 family.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:43.24,0:29:44.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Importantly, it also means using
Dialogue: 0,0:29:44.70,0:29:46.19,Default,,0,0,0,,key exchange algorithms that
Dialogue: 0,0:29:46.19,0:29:47.37,Default,,0,0,0,,provide forward secrecy.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:47.37,0:29:49.23,Default,,0,0,0,,And this is an increasingly
Dialogue: 0,0:29:49.23,0:29:50.57,Default,,0,0,0,,important property in today's
Dialogue: 0,0:29:50.57,0:29:54.16,Default,,0,0,0,,day where the content of your
Dialogue: 0,0:29:54.16,0:29:56.49,Default,,0,0,0,,application's data as
Dialogue: 0,0:29:56.49,0:29:58.39,Default,,0,0,0,,transmitted over the network are
Dialogue: 0,0:29:58.39,0:29:59.93,Default,,0,0,0,,kept save, even in the event
Dialogue: 0,0:29:59.93,0:30:01.14,Default,,0,0,0,,that the long-term private key
Dialogue: 0,0:30:01.14,0:30:02.38,Default,,0,0,0,,of a server is compromised.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:03.71,0:30:05.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, we live in a world where
Dialogue: 0,0:30:05.57,0:30:07.28,Default,,0,0,0,,not all TL servers are equal,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:07.47,0:30:09.27,Default,,0,0,0,,and moreover, not all TLS
Dialogue: 0,0:30:09.27,0:30:10.81,Default,,0,0,0,,servers use the same version or
Dialogue: 0,0:30:10.81,0:30:11.59,Default,,0,0,0,,configuration.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:12.30,0:30:14.42,Default,,0,0,0,,For example, you might have to
Dialogue: 0,0:30:14.42,0:30:15.65,Default,,0,0,0,,connect to an add server that
Dialogue: 0,0:30:15.65,0:30:17.14,Default,,0,0,0,,doesn't even support HTTPS.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:18.03,0:30:18.98,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what do you do?
Dialogue: 0,0:30:20.03,0:30:21.14,Default,,0,0,0,,This is where exceptions come
Dialogue: 0,0:30:21.14,0:30:21.37,Default,,0,0,0,,in.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:22.26,0:30:24.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Exceptions allow your app to opt
Dialogue: 0,0:30:24.70,0:30:26.92,Default,,0,0,0,,out of ATS enforcement for
Dialogue: 0,0:30:26.92,0:30:29.50,Default,,0,0,0,,particular domains, or globally
Dialogue: 0,0:30:29.50,0:30:30.55,Default,,0,0,0,,across your application.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:32.03,0:30:33.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Exceptions are intended to be
Dialogue: 0,0:30:33.92,0:30:35.93,Default,,0,0,0,,temporary to help you maintain
Dialogue: 0,0:30:35.93,0:30:37.72,Default,,0,0,0,,functionality while servers
Dialogue: 0,0:30:37.72,0:30:39.46,Default,,0,0,0,,upgrade to more modern TLS
Dialogue: 0,0:30:39.46,0:30:40.43,Default,,0,0,0,,configurations.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:42.00,0:30:43.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Last year, we announced plans to
Dialogue: 0,0:30:43.82,0:30:45.49,Default,,0,0,0,,start requiring justification
Dialogue: 0,0:30:45.49,0:30:47.45,Default,,0,0,0,,for exceptions in the app store.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:48.59,0:30:50.71,Default,,0,0,0,,And since then, we've heard that
Dialogue: 0,0:30:50.71,0:30:51.95,Default,,0,0,0,,the exceptions we had available
Dialogue: 0,0:30:51.95,0:30:53.69,Default,,0,0,0,,to you did not adequately meet
Dialogue: 0,0:30:53.85,0:30:54.98,Default,,0,0,0,,all of your use cases.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:55.66,0:30:58.33,Default,,0,0,0,,And since universal ATS adoption
Dialogue: 0,0:30:58.33,0:31:01.22,Default,,0,0,0,,remains our primary goal, we've
Dialogue: 0,0:31:01.22,0:31:03.06,Default,,0,0,0,,taken that time to update the
Dialogue: 0,0:31:03.06,0:31:03.87,Default,,0,0,0,,exceptions that we have
Dialogue: 0,0:31:03.87,0:31:05.85,Default,,0,0,0,,available to you to meet and
Dialogue: 0,0:31:05.85,0:31:07.21,Default,,0,0,0,,satisfy these use cases.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:07.58,0:31:08.77,Default,,0,0,0,,And I want to dive into some
Dialogue: 0,0:31:08.77,0:31:10.60,Default,,0,0,0,,recent ones that were added in
Dialogue: 0,0:31:10.60,0:31:11.08,Default,,0,0,0,,the past.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:11.87,0:31:13.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Specifically, we've gone beyond
Dialogue: 0,0:31:13.54,0:31:14.75,Default,,0,0,0,,just acceptance for WebKit
Dialogue: 0,0:31:14.75,0:31:15.20,Default,,0,0,0,,content.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:16.02,0:31:17.12,Default,,0,0,0,,There are exceptions now to
Dialogue: 0,0:31:17.12,0:31:18.92,Default,,0,0,0,,ensure that if you are streaming
Dialogue: 0,0:31:18.92,0:31:20.18,Default,,0,0,0,,data through the AVFoundation
Dialogue: 0,0:31:20.18,0:31:21.41,Default,,0,0,0,,framework that happens to be
Dialogue: 0,0:31:21.41,0:31:23.18,Default,,0,0,0,,encrypted at rest, you can opt
Dialogue: 0,0:31:23.18,0:31:24.52,Default,,0,0,0,,out of ATS for that particular
Dialogue: 0,0:31:24.52,0:31:24.86,Default,,0,0,0,,data.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:25.86,0:31:26.96,Default,,0,0,0,,We also have exceptions to
Dialogue: 0,0:31:26.96,0:31:29.46,Default,,0,0,0,,support opting out of ATS for
Dialogue: 0,0:31:29.46,0:31:31.88,Default,,0,0,0,,arbitrary WebView request and
Dialogue: 0,0:31:32.04,0:31:33.71,Default,,0,0,0,,opting out of ATS for local
Dialogue: 0,0:31:33.71,0:31:34.55,Default,,0,0,0,,network connections.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:35.41,0:31:36.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Here, local network connections
Dialogue: 0,0:31:36.55,0:31:37.94,Default,,0,0,0,,is just a connection made to a
Dialogue: 0,0:31:37.94,0:31:39.99,Default,,0,0,0,,raw IP address, or a server with
Dialogue: 0,0:31:39.99,0:31:41.29,Default,,0,0,0,,an unqualified domain name.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:42.52,0:31:44.99,Default,,0,0,0,,I want to be clear, even though
Dialogue: 0,0:31:44.99,0:31:46.40,Default,,0,0,0,,it may not be necessary for the
Dialogue: 0,0:31:46.40,0:31:47.43,Default,,0,0,0,,security and privacy of your
Dialogue: 0,0:31:47.43,0:31:50.10,Default,,0,0,0,,data to opt out of ATS, because
Dialogue: 0,0:31:50.10,0:31:51.43,Default,,0,0,0,,you have otherwise encrypted
Dialogue: 0,0:31:51.43,0:31:52.68,Default,,0,0,0,,your data before transmitting
Dialogue: 0,0:31:52.68,0:31:53.05,Default,,0,0,0,,it.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:53.48,0:31:54.70,Default,,0,0,0,,We still believe that the right
Dialogue: 0,0:31:54.70,0:31:56.90,Default,,0,0,0,,and proper thing to do is to use
Dialogue: 0,0:31:56.90,0:31:58.32,Default,,0,0,0,,TLS to protect your data in
Dialogue: 0,0:31:58.32,0:31:58.77,Default,,0,0,0,,transit.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:58.94,0:32:00.94,Default,,0,0,0,,That means as app developers,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:01.05,0:32:02.17,Default,,0,0,0,,and as Bailey already mentioned,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:02.71,0:32:04.37,Default,,0,0,0,,your goal should be to minimize
Dialogue: 0,0:32:04.41,0:32:06.24,Default,,0,0,0,,or remove exceptions where at
Dialogue: 0,0:32:06.24,0:32:08.03,Default,,0,0,0,,all possible, if it is within
Dialogue: 0,0:32:08.03,0:32:09.50,Default,,0,0,0,,your power to do so.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:10.27,0:32:12.02,Default,,0,0,0,,I also want to point out a
Dialogue: 0,0:32:12.02,0:32:13.55,Default,,0,0,0,,recent key that was added to
Dialogue: 0,0:32:13.55,0:32:14.41,Default,,0,0,0,,support certificate
Dialogue: 0,0:32:14.41,0:32:15.14,Default,,0,0,0,,transparency.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:16.31,0:32:18.13,Default,,0,0,0,,If you want a particular server
Dialogue: 0,0:32:18.13,0:32:20.76,Default,,0,0,0,,to opt into or participate in
Dialogue: 0,0:32:20.76,0:32:22.26,Default,,0,0,0,,certificate transparency to help
Dialogue: 0,0:32:22.26,0:32:24.24,Default,,0,0,0,,protect your apps, and users'
Dialogue: 0,0:32:24.24,0:32:27.96,Default,,0,0,0,,apps against certificate
Dialogue: 0,0:32:27.96,0:32:29.40,Default,,0,0,0,,[inaudible] attacks, you can
Dialogue: 0,0:32:29.40,0:32:31.45,Default,,0,0,0,,specify for a particular domain
Dialogue: 0,0:32:31.74,0:32:32.70,Default,,0,0,0,,whether or not you want that
Dialogue: 0,0:32:32.70,0:32:35.77,Default,,0,0,0,,server to participate in CT.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:36.16,0:32:38.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, we remain committed to ATS.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:39.71,0:32:41.15,Default,,0,0,0,,And in the past year we've
Dialogue: 0,0:32:41.15,0:32:43.09,Default,,0,0,0,,continued upgrading the services
Dialogue: 0,0:32:43.37,0:32:44.44,Default,,0,0,0,,that we make available to you as
Dialogue: 0,0:32:44.44,0:32:45.61,Default,,0,0,0,,developers, to make sure that
Dialogue: 0,0:32:45.61,0:32:46.67,Default,,0,0,0,,they are ATS compliant.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:47.51,0:32:48.87,Default,,0,0,0,,All the services you see here
Dialogue: 0,0:32:49.06,0:32:50.97,Default,,0,0,0,,are fully ATS compliant, meaning
Dialogue: 0,0:32:50.97,0:32:51.94,Default,,0,0,0,,that your apps will not have to
Dialogue: 0,0:32:51.94,0:32:53.70,Default,,0,0,0,,specify and exceptions when
Dialogue: 0,0:32:53.70,0:32:54.37,Default,,0,0,0,,talking to them.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:55.27,0:32:56.61,Default,,0,0,0,,You get best practice network
Dialogue: 0,0:32:56.61,0:32:58.58,Default,,0,0,0,,security out of the box, which
Dialogue: 0,0:32:58.58,0:32:59.44,Default,,0,0,0,,is the ultimate goal.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:00.87,0:33:02.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, also in this past year, we
Dialogue: 0,0:33:02.00,0:33:04.69,Default,,0,0,0,,kept an eye on the app store to
Dialogue: 0,0:33:04.74,0:33:06.93,Default,,0,0,0,,track and see how ATS adoption
Dialogue: 0,0:33:07.56,0:33:08.39,Default,,0,0,0,,is going.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:08.55,0:33:10.70,Default,,0,0,0,,We see adoption increasing.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:11.62,0:33:13.19,Default,,0,0,0,,We've also been seeing the
Dialogue: 0,0:33:13.19,0:33:14.48,Default,,0,0,0,,number of exceptions increasing.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:14.92,0:33:15.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Which means that there's still
Dialogue: 0,0:33:15.80,0:33:16.75,Default,,0,0,0,,more work to be done.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:17.54,0:33:18.84,Default,,0,0,0,,If you are an app developer,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:19.26,0:33:21.04,Default,,0,0,0,,continue to be vigilant and
Dialogue: 0,0:33:21.04,0:33:23.31,Default,,0,0,0,,remove, or minimize your reliant
Dialogue: 0,0:33:23.31,0:33:24.03,Default,,0,0,0,,on exceptions.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:24.57,0:33:26.25,Default,,0,0,0,,If you are a server operator or
Dialogue: 0,0:33:26.25,0:33:29.15,Default,,0,0,0,,owner, please continue upgrading
Dialogue: 0,0:33:29.15,0:33:30.37,Default,,0,0,0,,your server configurations to
Dialogue: 0,0:33:30.37,0:33:32.73,Default,,0,0,0,,support 1.2 and more modern
Dialogue: 0,0:33:32.73,0:33:35.22,Default,,0,0,0,,versions of TLS.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:35.44,0:33:39.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, speaking of TLS, I want to
Dialogue: 0,0:33:39.49,0:33:41.00,Default,,0,0,0,,give you a brief glimpse into
Dialogue: 0,0:33:41.00,0:33:42.23,Default,,0,0,0,,the future of this critical
Dialogue: 0,0:33:42.26,0:33:43.16,Default,,0,0,0,,security protocol.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:44.24,0:33:45.31,Default,,0,0,0,,For those of you who don't know,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:45.63,0:33:47.26,Default,,0,0,0,,TLS is quickly becoming the
Dialogue: 0,0:33:47.26,0:33:48.11,Default,,0,0,0,,[inaudible] of the internet.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:48.58,0:33:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,More and more of your traffic is
Dialogue: 0,0:33:50.04,0:33:52.62,Default,,0,0,0,,protected on the wire thanks to
Dialogue: 0,0:33:52.62,0:33:53.23,Default,,0,0,0,,TLS, today.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:54.87,0:33:57.23,Default,,0,0,0,,However, not all traffic is
Dialogue: 0,0:33:57.23,0:33:58.07,Default,,0,0,0,,protected the same.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:59.03,0:34:00.19,Default,,0,0,0,,This protocol has been with us
Dialogue: 0,0:34:00.19,0:34:01.93,Default,,0,0,0,,for many, many years and there
Dialogue: 0,0:34:01.93,0:34:02.58,Default,,0,0,0,,are many different
Dialogue: 0,0:34:02.58,0:34:03.73,Default,,0,0,0,,implementations and
Dialogue: 0,0:34:03.73,0:34:05.17,Default,,0,0,0,,configurations of servers out
Dialogue: 0,0:34:05.17,0:34:06.75,Default,,0,0,0,,there supporting a wide variety
Dialogue: 0,0:34:06.75,0:34:08.28,Default,,0,0,0,,of TLS versions.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:09.64,0:34:11.13,Default,,0,0,0,,And over time the protocol has
Dialogue: 0,0:34:11.13,0:34:12.62,Default,,0,0,0,,been patched and amended to
Dialogue: 0,0:34:12.62,0:34:13.84,Default,,0,0,0,,generally address some of the
Dialogue: 0,0:34:13.84,0:34:15.05,Default,,0,0,0,,attacks that Bailey eluded to
Dialogue: 0,0:34:15.05,0:34:17.17,Default,,0,0,0,,earlier and just to fix up
Dialogue: 0,0:34:17.17,0:34:18.18,Default,,0,0,0,,general deficiency in the
Dialogue: 0,0:34:18.18,0:34:18.65,Default,,0,0,0,,protocol.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:19.78,0:34:21.12,Default,,0,0,0,,In recent years, the internet
Dialogue: 0,0:34:21.12,0:34:22.06,Default,,0,0,0,,community has taken it upon
Dialogue: 0,0:34:22.06,0:34:23.00,Default,,0,0,0,,themselves and deemed it
Dialogue: 0,0:34:23.00,0:34:24.22,Default,,0,0,0,,necessary to start working on
Dialogue: 0,0:34:24.22,0:34:25.10,Default,,0,0,0,,the next version of this
Dialogue: 0,0:34:25.57,0:34:26.44,Default,,0,0,0,,critical protocol.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:27.89,0:34:30.82,Default,,0,0,0,,TLS 1.3. And in the spirit of
Dialogue: 0,0:34:30.82,0:34:32.68,Default,,0,0,0,,best practices, we are closely
Dialogue: 0,0:34:32.68,0:34:33.98,Default,,0,0,0,,tracking this work to ensure
Dialogue: 0,0:34:33.98,0:34:35.76,Default,,0,0,0,,that we are ready to adopt it
Dialogue: 0,0:34:36.02,0:34:37.92,Default,,0,0,0,,and help you adopt it when it
Dialogue: 0,0:34:37.92,0:34:40.28,Default,,0,0,0,,becomes a standard.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:40.40,0:34:42.48,Default,,0,0,0,,TLS 1.3 is truly best practice
Dialogue: 0,0:34:42.48,0:34:43.13,Default,,0,0,0,,by design.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:44.16,0:34:45.49,Default,,0,0,0,,All of the features, the
Dialogue: 0,0:34:45.49,0:34:46.58,Default,,0,0,0,,majority of the features that
Dialogue: 0,0:34:46.58,0:34:47.88,Default,,0,0,0,,are in ATS compliance
Dialogue: 0,0:34:47.88,0:34:49.94,Default,,0,0,0,,configurations are simply part
Dialogue: 0,0:34:49.94,0:34:50.83,Default,,0,0,0,,of the core standard.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:52.02,0:34:54.14,Default,,0,0,0,,That means legacy cryptographic
Dialogue: 0,0:34:54.14,0:34:55.76,Default,,0,0,0,,cipher suites, hash functions,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:55.76,0:34:56.91,Default,,0,0,0,,and key exchange algorithms are
Dialogue: 0,0:34:56.91,0:34:58.32,Default,,0,0,0,,simply not allowed.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:58.61,0:34:59.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Not that you shouldn't use them,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:00.02,0:35:01.25,Default,,0,0,0,,they're just not there to begin
Dialogue: 0,0:35:01.25,0:35:01.43,Default,,0,0,0,,with.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:02.50,0:35:03.85,Default,,0,0,0,,That means the specification is
Dialogue: 0,0:35:03.89,0:35:05.00,Default,,0,0,0,,overall much simpler.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:05.79,0:35:06.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Which means that it's easier to
Dialogue: 0,0:35:06.73,0:35:09.00,Default,,0,0,0,,implement, easier to reason
Dialogue: 0,0:35:09.00,0:35:10.86,Default,,0,0,0,,about, and most importantly
Dialogue: 0,0:35:11.12,0:35:11.96,Default,,0,0,0,,easier to test.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:12.13,0:35:13.74,Default,,0,0,0,,And this gives us greater
Dialogue: 0,0:35:13.74,0:35:15.04,Default,,0,0,0,,confidence that the
Dialogue: 0,0:35:15.04,0:35:17.10,Default,,0,0,0,,implementation is free, or at
Dialogue: 0,0:35:17.10,0:35:19.93,Default,,0,0,0,,least has very few problems that
Dialogue: 0,0:35:19.93,0:35:21.26,Default,,0,0,0,,have plagued TLS libraries in
Dialogue: 0,0:35:22.00,0:35:23.84,Default,,0,0,0,,the past.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:23.99,0:35:25.63,Default,,0,0,0,,As a result of this simplicity,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:26.35,0:35:27.60,Default,,0,0,0,,it also has improved network
Dialogue: 0,0:35:27.60,0:35:28.25,Default,,0,0,0,,efficiency.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:29.10,0:35:30.13,Default,,0,0,0,,And let me show you what I mean
Dialogue: 0,0:35:30.96,0:35:31.79,Default,,0,0,0,,by that.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:31.94,0:35:32.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's walk through a typical
Dialogue: 0,0:35:32.84,0:35:35.98,Default,,0,0,0,,handshake in TLS 1.2 and 1.3 to
Dialogue: 0,0:35:35.98,0:35:37.12,Default,,0,0,0,,establish a connection to a
Dialogue: 0,0:35:37.12,0:35:37.53,Default,,0,0,0,,server.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:38.14,0:35:41.80,Default,,0,0,0,,We start with a TCP connection,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:42.22,0:35:43.41,Default,,0,0,0,,which requires one round trip
Dialogue: 0,0:35:43.41,0:35:44.18,Default,,0,0,0,,between the client and the
Dialogue: 0,0:35:44.18,0:35:44.51,Default,,0,0,0,,server.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:45.88,0:35:47.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Next step you start your TLS
Dialogue: 0,0:35:47.03,0:35:48.91,Default,,0,0,0,,handshake, where the client and
Dialogue: 0,0:35:48.91,0:35:50.11,Default,,0,0,0,,server exchange some hellos and
Dialogue: 0,0:35:50.11,0:35:51.67,Default,,0,0,0,,some initial centrifugation
Dialogue: 0,0:35:51.67,0:35:54.48,Default,,0,0,0,,information needed to proceed
Dialogue: 0,0:35:54.48,0:35:55.55,Default,,0,0,0,,with the rest of the connection.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:56.25,0:35:58.81,Default,,0,0,0,,In TLS 1.3, they actually start
Dialogue: 0,0:35:58.81,0:36:00.76,Default,,0,0,0,,also negotiating key material
Dialogue: 0,0:36:00.90,0:36:03.26,Default,,0,0,0,,used to encrypt the rest of the
Dialogue: 0,0:36:03.26,0:36:05.48,Default,,0,0,0,,traffic sent over that section,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:06.00,0:36:07.07,Default,,0,0,0,,which means that in the next
Dialogue: 0,0:36:07.07,0:36:08.59,Default,,0,0,0,,round, the client can start
Dialogue: 0,0:36:08.59,0:36:09.73,Default,,0,0,0,,sending application data.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:10.92,0:36:13.54,Default,,0,0,0,,In 1.2, the client and server
Dialogue: 0,0:36:13.54,0:36:14.47,Default,,0,0,0,,are still negotiating key
Dialogue: 0,0:36:14.47,0:36:16.32,Default,,0,0,0,,material, which means that
Dialogue: 0,0:36:16.32,0:36:18.90,Default,,0,0,0,,requires one more round trip to
Dialogue: 0,0:36:18.90,0:36:20.57,Default,,0,0,0,,establish this session and start
Dialogue: 0,0:36:20.57,0:36:21.17,Default,,0,0,0,,sending data.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:22.46,0:36:23.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, this may not seem like a
Dialogue: 0,0:36:23.48,0:36:24.81,Default,,0,0,0,,lot, but let me put it in
Dialogue: 0,0:36:24.81,0:36:25.60,Default,,0,0,0,,perspective for you.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:26.55,0:36:27.79,Default,,0,0,0,,We collect data from a wide
Dialogue: 0,0:36:27.79,0:36:30.36,Default,,0,0,0,,variety of devices on different
Dialogue: 0,0:36:30.36,0:36:32.98,Default,,0,0,0,,networks, both carrier, cellular
Dialogue: 0,0:36:33.13,0:36:34.42,Default,,0,0,0,,and wi-fi around the world.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:34.47,0:36:36.87,Default,,0,0,0,,And our data suggests that at
Dialogue: 0,0:36:36.87,0:36:38.43,Default,,0,0,0,,least 10% of cellular
Dialogue: 0,0:36:38.43,0:36:41.57,Default,,0,0,0,,connections, or at least 10% of
Dialogue: 0,0:36:41.57,0:36:42.85,Default,,0,0,0,,TLS connections on cellular
Dialogue: 0,0:36:42.85,0:36:44.24,Default,,0,0,0,,networks, rather, require at
Dialogue: 0,0:36:44.24,0:36:45.64,Default,,0,0,0,,least 800 milliseconds to
Dialogue: 0,0:36:45.64,0:36:46.24,Default,,0,0,0,,complete.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:46.81,0:36:49.21,Default,,0,0,0,,And 10% of TLS connections on
Dialogue: 0,0:36:49.21,0:36:50.97,Default,,0,0,0,,wi-fi networks take 500
Dialogue: 0,0:36:50.97,0:36:51.95,Default,,0,0,0,,milliseconds to complete.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:53.03,0:36:55.57,Default,,0,0,0,,TLS 1.3 would effectively shave
Dialogue: 0,0:36:55.57,0:36:57.68,Default,,0,0,0,,1/3 of that time off, which is a
Dialogue: 0,0:36:57.68,0:37:00.91,Default,,0,0,0,,huge win in mobile world.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:01.52,0:37:05.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, TLS 1.3 is still very much
Dialogue: 0,0:37:05.04,0:37:05.97,Default,,0,0,0,,a work in progress.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:06.03,0:37:08.16,Default,,0,0,0,,And that's why ATS compliance is
Dialogue: 0,0:37:08.16,0:37:10.04,Default,,0,0,0,,still focused on getting you to
Dialogue: 0,0:37:10.04,0:37:12.05,Default,,0,0,0,,1.2, and ensuring that you're
Dialogue: 0,0:37:12.05,0:37:13.96,Default,,0,0,0,,using the latest proper standard
Dialogue: 0,0:37:13.96,0:37:14.54,Default,,0,0,0,,of the protocol.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:15.56,0:37:17.81,Default,,0,0,0,,However, if you want to
Dialogue: 0,0:37:17.81,0:37:19.66,Default,,0,0,0,,experiment with TLS 1.3 to
Dialogue: 0,0:37:19.66,0:37:20.64,Default,,0,0,0,,prepare yourself for this
Dialogue: 0,0:37:20.64,0:37:22.40,Default,,0,0,0,,protocol, I'm pleased to
Dialogue: 0,0:37:22.45,0:37:24.71,Default,,0,0,0,,announce that we can now allow
Dialogue: 0,0:37:24.71,0:37:25.38,Default,,0,0,0,,you to do that.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:26.34,0:37:27.93,Default,,0,0,0,,It is not on by default in any
Dialogue: 0,0:37:27.93,0:37:28.66,Default,,0,0,0,,of our systems.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:29.30,0:37:31.04,Default,,0,0,0,,However, if you opt into the
Dialogue: 0,0:37:31.04,0:37:33.58,Default,,0,0,0,,seed and want to start
Dialogue: 0,0:37:33.58,0:37:35.18,Default,,0,0,0,,experimenting with it, you can
Dialogue: 0,0:37:35.18,0:37:39.60,Default,,0,0,0,,install a profile on iOS, or
Dialogue: 0,0:37:39.60,0:37:41.23,Default,,0,0,0,,enable system wide TLS 1.3 on
Dialogue: 0,0:37:41.23,0:37:42.87,Default,,0,0,0,,macOS with the simple defaults
Dialogue: 0,0:37:43.57,0:37:43.67,Default,,0,0,0,,write.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:44.29,0:37:46.74,Default,,0,0,0,,And you would do this to prime
Dialogue: 0,0:37:46.74,0:37:47.92,Default,,0,0,0,,your application and your
Dialogue: 0,0:37:47.92,0:37:49.72,Default,,0,0,0,,network as the protocol marches
Dialogue: 0,0:37:49.72,0:37:51.06,Default,,0,0,0,,toward standardization in the
Dialogue: 0,0:37:51.06,0:37:51.59,Default,,0,0,0,,next year.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:52.12,0:37:54.40,Default,,0,0,0,,And in the meantime, we're
Dialogue: 0,0:37:54.40,0:37:56.52,Default,,0,0,0,,paying our due diligence and
Dialogue: 0,0:37:56.52,0:37:58.06,Default,,0,0,0,,working with third parties and
Dialogue: 0,0:37:58.06,0:37:59.29,Default,,0,0,0,,with our enterprise partners to
Dialogue: 0,0:37:59.29,0:38:01.92,Default,,0,0,0,,ensure their apps and their
Dialogue: 0,0:38:01.92,0:38:02.88,Default,,0,0,0,,networks are ready for the
Dialogue: 0,0:38:02.88,0:38:04.75,Default,,0,0,0,,adoption of the protocol as
Dialogue: 0,0:38:05.74,0:38:05.86,Default,,0,0,0,,well.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:07.30,0:38:08.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, I want to take a step back
Dialogue: 0,0:38:08.42,0:38:09.72,Default,,0,0,0,,and come full circle with
Dialogue: 0,0:38:09.72,0:38:11.33,Default,,0,0,0,,everything Bailey and I talked
Dialogue: 0,0:38:11.83,0:38:13.36,Default,,0,0,0,,about today.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:13.55,0:38:15.56,Default,,0,0,0,,One of our primary objectives is
Dialogue: 0,0:38:15.56,0:38:17.30,Default,,0,0,0,,to help you keep your customers'
Dialogue: 0,0:38:17.30,0:38:18.45,Default,,0,0,0,,data secure and private.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:19.38,0:38:20.70,Default,,0,0,0,,And we do this by giving you
Dialogue: 0,0:38:20.70,0:38:21.68,Default,,0,0,0,,best practice tools and
Dialogue: 0,0:38:21.68,0:38:23.12,Default,,0,0,0,,technologies to help achieve
Dialogue: 0,0:38:23.23,0:38:23.72,Default,,0,0,0,,that goal.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:24.99,0:38:26.33,Default,,0,0,0,,However, you need to do some
Dialogue: 0,0:38:26.33,0:38:27.02,Default,,0,0,0,,work yourself.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:27.65,0:38:29.26,Default,,0,0,0,,And that means avoiding legacy
Dialogue: 0,0:38:29.26,0:38:30.82,Default,,0,0,0,,or deprecated algorithms when at
Dialogue: 0,0:38:30.82,0:38:31.50,Default,,0,0,0,,all possible.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:31.70,0:38:33.67,Default,,0,0,0,,And it also means continuing to
Dialogue: 0,0:38:33.67,0:38:34.69,Default,,0,0,0,,upgrade to modern TLS
Dialogue: 0,0:38:34.69,0:38:35.55,Default,,0,0,0,,configurations.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:36.87,0:38:37.73,Default,,0,0,0,,If you're a server owner,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:37.73,0:38:39.92,Default,,0,0,0,,operator, again, that means
Dialogue: 0,0:38:39.92,0:38:42.10,Default,,0,0,0,,moving to 1.2 to make sure that
Dialogue: 0,0:38:42.10,0:38:44.41,Default,,0,0,0,,every app that is ATS compliant
Dialogue: 0,0:38:44.41,0:38:45.02,Default,,0,0,0,,can speak to you.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:46.23,0:38:47.36,Default,,0,0,0,,If you're an app developer,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:47.36,0:38:49.53,Default,,0,0,0,,again, that means minimizing or
Dialogue: 0,0:38:49.53,0:38:51.07,Default,,0,0,0,,reducing the use of exceptions.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:52.67,0:38:53.57,Default,,0,0,0,,And if you're particularly
Dialogue: 0,0:38:53.57,0:38:55.37,Default,,0,0,0,,adventurous, that means also
Dialogue: 0,0:38:55.37,0:38:57.98,Default,,0,0,0,,trying out TLS 1.3 to prime your
Dialogue: 0,0:38:57.98,0:38:59.96,Default,,0,0,0,,application and your network for
Dialogue: 0,0:38:59.96,0:39:01.00,Default,,0,0,0,,the next exciting version of
Dialogue: 0,0:39:01.00,0:39:01.54,Default,,0,0,0,,this protocol.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:02.12,0:39:05.74,Default,,0,0,0,,If you'd like any more
Dialogue: 0,0:39:05.74,0:39:07.89,Default,,0,0,0,,information on any of the topics
Dialogue: 0,0:39:07.89,0:39:09.31,Default,,0,0,0,,that Bailey and I discussed, you
Dialogue: 0,0:39:09.31,0:39:10.33,Default,,0,0,0,,can visit this link above.
